<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Demands U.S., S. Korea Apology on Submarine Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) on Thursday held the United States and South Korea
responsible for the suicide of nine crewmen in a DPRK submarine.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant General Ri Chan Bok, of the Korean People's Army of
the DPRK, demanded apology from the United States and South Korea
at a meeting with the United Nations Command in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the third one between general-level officers, was
held in Panmunjom, the armistice village in the demilitarized zone
separating the Korean Peninsula into the DPRK and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Ri, senior delegate of the DPRK side, was quoted by the Korean
Central News Agency as saying that the submarine was wrecked in
open seas due to an engine trouble during a routine training on
June 22.
</P>
<P>
Far from taking measures to rescue the wrecked submarine under
international law, Ri said, South Korea sent warships and aircraft
in indiscriminate attack, "so that the submarine overturned."
</P>
<P>
South Korean soldiers broke the aerial of the submarine and
pulled it for a long time before it sank, he said, adding that the
crewmen "had no alternative but to kill themselves," as they were
unable to send out distress signals.
</P>
<P>
However, South Korea said earlier the submarine infiltrated
into its waters, violating the armistice that ended the Korean War
in 1953.
</P>
<P>
South Korea also found a body on the sea off its Kangwon
Province on July 12. Seoul believes the dead man was a DPRK
infiltrator.
</P>
<P>
It is ridiculous that Seoul described the man as an "armed spy
who intruded into South Korea," said Ri.
</P>
<P>
He also urged Seoul to return the submarine at an early date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sam Rainsy Calls for Demilitarized Election Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 16 (Xinhua) -- One of Cambodia's opposition
leaders, Sam Rainsy, appeals to the government Wednesday for
demilitarization of election process and neutrality of police and
military forces during the July 26 elections.
</P>
<P>
"Aware of an increase in military movement in various parts of
Cambodia, the Sam Rainsy Party appeals to the present government
to allow the electoral process to proceed without violence,
intimidation or involvement of military and police forces in the
electoral process," Sam Rainsy said.
</P>
<P>
All sides should not use troops for partisan political
purposes, and all military and police forces should be loyal to
the nation instead of any political party or political leader, the
president of Sam Rainsy Party said.
</P>
<P>
Sam Rainsy also pledges that his party "will strive for
national reconciliation and the integration of all armed forces
into a neutral Royal Cambodian Armed Forces, loyal only to the
nation and people of Cambodia under the Constitution."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
