<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Deputy Secretary of State to visit Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott is expected to arrive here on July 22 on a two-day
visit to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Talbott will hold talks with the
Pakistani leadership and spell out Washington's stance on various
issues relating to the post-nuclear tests situation in South Asia
with particular reference to its non-proliferation objectives,
official sources said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, the sources said that Pakistani leaders will
apprise Talbott about the necessity of steps Islamabad took in May
to safeguard its security concerns in the face of Indian
provocation .
</P>
<P>
Pakistan believes that the Kashmir issue is the root-cause of
tension in South Asia, the sources said, adding that the U.S. and
other permanent members of the U.N. Security Council recognized
the urgency of resolving the Kashmir issue in their meetings held
after the nuclear tests by India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the issue of the International
Monetary Fund's holding back its loan of 226 million U.S. dollars
to Pakistan will also be under discussions between Talbott and the
Pakistani leadership.
</P>
<P>
Talbott's visit will take place a few days after the Clinton
Administration got broad authority to temporarily lift all
economic sanctions against Pakistan and India imposed following
their nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has welcomed it as "a positive step which will
eventually lead to lifting of all economic sanctions."
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Office Spokesman said Wednesday that "a cooperative
approach which gives recognition and understanding to mutual
concerns will work better than a coercive approach which is always
counter-productive."
</P>
<P>
Before arriving here on July 22, Talbott will visit India on
July 20-21 and hold discussions with the Indian leadership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Industrial Production Falls Sharply in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. industrial production
fell 0.6 percent in June, the steepest drop in five years, the
Federal Reserve reported here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The monthly decline was the sharpest since the index fell 0.9
percent in March 1991.
</P>
<P>
However, most of the decline was attributed to an 11 percent
dropoff in automotive production, blamed mainly for the lingering
GM strike, started from June 5.
</P>
<P>
Outside of the auto industry, the performance was lackluster.
Output at factories other than auto, trucks and parts plants rose
just 0.1 percent in June following a 0.1 percent decline in May.
Utility output increased 0.4 percent in June while production at
mines and oil wells fell 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The overall drop in industrial production was larger than
economists expected from the GM strike alone and fit with the
notion that Asia's economic turmoil is slowing the U.S. economy by
knocking down demand for U.S. exports to the region.
</P>
<P>
The operating rate at industrial firms ran at 81.6 percent of
capacity, the lowest in five years and down from 82.4 percent in
May. Just at factories, the operating rate declined to 80.3
percent, also the lowest in five years and down from 81.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
That's been reflected in recent inflation reports, which show
prices virtually unchanged for goods but up at a moderate rate of
nearly 3 percent for services, which are feeling the squeeze of
labor shortages in many occupations.
</P>
<P>
Despite the overall weakness of June's report, there were
area's of strength. Industrial equipment production shot up 2.2
percent, with strong increases for construction machinery, farm
machinery and computers and other office equipment. Semiconductor
and clothing output also rose.
</P>
<P>
However, production of home appliances and carpeting fell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coca-Cola Sales up 10 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Coca-Cola Company reported
Thursday that its second-quarter unit case volume increased 10
percent with share of sales continuing to expand both in the
United States and throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Its worldwide unit case volume increased 12 percent for the
first six months of the year. Worldwide gallon shipments grew 9
percent for the second quarter and have grown 12 percent for the
first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The company reported its net income at 1.191 billion U.S.
dollars for the second quarter, a 9 percent increase over the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In its regional growth, Latin America saw the largest
increase of 12 percent in the second quarter and Asia market had
only 7 percent increase for its sales.
</P>
<P>
However, India and China continued leading the world in
consuming Coca-Cola. Unit case volume jumped 33 percent and 28
percent respectively in these two countries in the April-June
period.
</P>
<P>
"Our performance across Asia is the result of four ability to
stay focused and adjust in these tough times -- keeping our
products within reach and offering value to customers and
consumers," said Douglas Ivester, chairman and chief executive
officer of the company.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
