<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Poetess Zoe Karelli Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Zoe Karelli, one of Greece's most
important female poets, died Thursday at her home in the northern
city of Thessaloniki at the age of 96.
</P>
<P>
Karelli's first work was published in 1935. Since then, she
published 12 poem collelctions. In her works, she eloquently wove
together images of the ancient Greek spirit and christianity.
</P>
<P>
In 1965, she was received a prestigious state award for her
"Kassandra" anthology and she won the state poetry award again in
1974. In 1988, the poetess was named honorary professor by the
Aristotle University's School of Philosophy and she was bestowed
by the President of Greece with the Palm Commander Award in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-16 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Wants to Warm up Relations with Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan
Thursday received a message from his Kuwaiti counterpart saying
the emirate wants better bilateral relations seven years after the
break-up of diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
In his message, Kuwaiti Crown Prince and Prime Minister Sheikh
Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Sabah expressed thanks for Jordan's recent
mediation effort for the release of Kuwaiti prisoners in Iraq,
calling it a good start for both sides to warm up relations.
</P>
<P>
"We appreciate your concern to do every possible effort to
(help) release the Kuwaiti prisoners and detained hostages in
Iraqi jails," Al-Sabah said.
</P>
<P>
Continued efforts and positive developments between Jordan and
Kuwait will enhance bilateral ties and further speed up its
restoration, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said future cooperation between Kuwait and Jordan is an
inexorable trend and part of the cooperation among the whole Arab
world.
</P>
<P>
He said he agreed with the Jordanian regent that international
developments make it imperative "on all of us to build our region
anew, establish codes of conducts and work out plans to
consolidate cooperation and defend our competitive position in the
world."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait is "fully ready to support and contribute to every
genuine effort geared to realize these Pan-Arab noble objectives
and reconstruct the joint Arab action on solid ambitions and
individual inclinations," he added.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait froze ties with Jordan after accusing it of supporting
Iraq during the latter's seven-month occupation of the emirate
between August 1990 and February 1991.
</P>
<P>
At the height of the crisis, Kuwait dismissed over 320,000
Jordanians from their jobs, closed the Jordanian Embassy and
recalled its ambassador from Amman.
</P>
<P>
The ice in Jordanian-Kuwaiti ties began to thaw in July 1997,
when both sides resumed commercial flights between their capital
cities.
</P>
<P>
The ties turned for the better in April this year, when Kuwait
released 13 Jordanian prisoners jailed since 1991 for allegedly
collaborating with Iraq during the Gulf war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Situation Aggravates in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Flooding in Bangladesh has
aggravated as water levels in major rivers rose and onrush hilly
waters and incessant rains engulfed more areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The flood situation may experience further deterioration
following a general rising trend of water levels in the major
rivers and significant rainfall in the upstream," the Flood
Forecasting and Warning Center said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Millions of people have been affected and vast areas of
standing crops have been washed away in many parts of the country,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
At least 22 people have been killed in the monsoon flooding in
the country, they said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina has expressed her deep concern at
the plight of flood-hit people and directed district
administrations to take all necessary measures to mitigate their
sufferings.
</P>
<P>
She asked district administrations to work out necessary
preparedness plans for evacuation of the flood-affected people and
cattle and for undertaking relief operations in the affected
areas.
</P>
<P>
The Disaster Management and Relief Ministry has sanctioned
grants for flood-stricken districts as relief. It has provided 350
tons of rice for some districts. In the southeastern Bandarban
hill district, the local administration has allocated 9.5 tons of
rice as emergency relief for flood-affected people.
</P>
<P>
More than 2 million people have been reportedly affected and
over 1 million acres of crops have been damaged by floods in
Bangladesh since the monsoon season began in July. The extent of
damage by the floods, however, is yet to be ascertained, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
There are frequent heavy rains in the monsoon season (from July
to October) in the South Asian nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawi's Tobacco to Bring in Dismal Earning: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Malawi's major foreign exchange
earner, tobacco, is estimated to bring in a dismal 6.7 billion
Kwacha (268 million US Dollars) this year, representing a 27
percent drop over last year's earnings.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco Control Commission (TCC) General Manager Godfrey
Chapola told the daily Times newspaper in Blantyre, the Malawi
News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"If the trend in prices is the same to the end of the
auctioning season, we estimate that 180 million US Dollars will
be realized from tobacco this year," said Chapola.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Malawi made 249 million Dollars from tobacco sales.
</P>
<P>
According to the tobacco commission chief, high production
costs such as a rise in fertilizer prices, has largely caused the
drop in the production of high fetching burley and flue cured
tobaccos.
</P>
<P>
"Thirteen percent of tobacco estate growers did not grow
burley this year while a number of them have now opted to become
intermediate buyers," he said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 113 million kilograms of tobacco is estimated to be
realized this year as opposed to 158 million kilograms in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Of the estimates, Chapola said Malawi's southern region is
expected to produce 16 million kilograms of burley tobacco,
representing a drop of 27 percent from the 1997 yield.
</P>
<P>
The central region is anticipated to produce 73 million
kilograms of burley against 98 million for last year. Northern
region which is the largest producer will yield 112 million
kilograms of burley as opposed to 134 million in 1997, with a
16-percent drop.
</P>
<P>
Of the flue cured tobacco, Chapola said, the southern region
which produced 3.98 million kilograms in 1997 is now expected to
produce 2.5 million kilograms. Central region will produce 7.5
million kilograms against the 9.1 million kilograms last year.
</P>
<P>
However, only the northern region will produce more flue cured
tobacco this year (2 million kilograms) than last year's 1.8
million kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Malawi is divided into three regions, namely southern, central
and northern regions.
</P>
<P>
As of July 2, Chapola said the average for burley at the
auction floors was 129 U.S. cents per kilogram while last year's
average price during the same period was 168 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Flue cured tobacco fetched 158 U.S. cents per kilogram as of
July 2 this year as compared to 180 cents in the same period in
1997. Due to the same dismal pricing, there has been an outcry
by many farmers especially small-scale producers who feel cheated
and would reap nothing in terms of profits as every cent realized
would go to payment of input loans.
</P>
<P>
Another contributing factor to the poor prices, according to
Chapola, is that much of the tobacco was damaged by the heavy
rains in the 1997/98 growing season.
</P>
<P>
"This also affected the quality of crop," lamented the tobacco
chief.
</P>
<P>
Some economic analysts feel it is high time Malawi shifted its
total dependence on tobacco for foreign exchange to other equally
profiting ventures especially in view of the escalating
anti-tobacco lobby internationally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
