<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Grants Assistance to Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Union has agreed to
provide a grant assistance of some 5.95 million U.S. dollars to
Nepal for implementing the Kathmandu Valley mapping project, the
Nepali RSS news agency said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to improve the capabilities and capacities of
the Kathmandu Municipality to carry out the comprehensive process
of urban development and management in a sustainable manner, the
RSS said.
</P>
<P>
It consists of urban planning mapping including both
topographical digital mapping and pilot cadastral technical
mapping, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The project, which covers the whole Kathmandu Valley with focus
on the Kathmandu city center, will be implemented over a six-year
period beginning from 1998, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandans Urged to Help Abducted Children Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The World Vision Uganda, a
non-governmental organization, is trying to bring the abducted
children in north Uganda to limelight and has appealed to
Ugandans and the world community to help the traumatized young
people.
</P>
<P>
Kofi Hagan, the country director of World Vision Uganda, told
a press conference here Thursday afternoon that his organization
has two centers in north Uganda whose duties are to help restore
hope in the children of reuniting with their communities.
</P>
<P>
He said some 4,000 to 6,000 children ranging from 10 to 20
years of age have been abducted by the rebels of the Lord's
Resistance Army since 1986.
</P>
<P>
Once abducted, the children would be forced to carry loads too
heavy for their backs, to be trained to kill and some of the
girls were given out to rebel commanders as rewards, he revealed.
</P>
<P>
Their center in Gulu district, set up in March 1995, has
offered skills training and psychological therapy to more than
3,500 children.
</P>
<P>
The center is facilitated by social workers, counselors,
health specialists, and vocational skills trainers.
</P>
<P>
"Many of them have lost so many years of education that it is
difficult for them to go back to school again and therefore
acquisition of basic skills prove very useful," he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
He called on all people to try to end the war in the country
so that people can be developed into productive force for the
society.
</P>
<P>
"Without the cessation of the war, there will be no end to the
abductions," he noted.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, a book named Restored Hope was issued to
all those present. It contains testimonies of 11 former abducted
children undergoing counseling in north Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawi's Tobacco to Bring in Dismal Earning: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Malawi's major foreign exchange
earner, tobacco, is estimated to bring in a dismal 6.7 billion
Kwacha (268 million US Dollars) this year, representing a 27
percent drop over last year's earnings.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco Control Commission (TCC) General Manager Godfrey
Chapola told the daily Times newspaper in Blantyre, the Malawi
News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"If the trend in prices is the same to the end of the
auctioning season, we estimate that 180 million US Dollars will
be realized from tobacco this year," said Chapola.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Malawi made 249 million Dollars from tobacco sales.
</P>
<P>
According to the tobacco commission chief, high production
costs such as a rise in fertilizer prices, has largely caused the
drop in the production of high fetching burley and flue cured
tobaccos.
</P>
<P>
"Thirteen percent of tobacco estate growers did not grow
burley this year while a number of them have now opted to become
intermediate buyers," he said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 113 million kilograms of tobacco is estimated to be
realized this year as opposed to 158 million kilograms in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Of the estimates, Chapola said Malawi's southern region is
expected to produce 16 million kilograms of burley tobacco,
representing a drop of 27 percent from the 1997 yield.
</P>
<P>
The central region is anticipated to produce 73 million
kilograms of burley against 98 million for last year. Northern
region which is the largest producer will yield 112 million
kilograms of burley as opposed to 134 million in 1997, with a
16-percent drop.
</P>
<P>
Of the flue cured tobacco, Chapola said, the southern region
which produced 3.98 million kilograms in 1997 is now expected to
produce 2.5 million kilograms. Central region will produce 7.5
million kilograms against the 9.1 million kilograms last year.
</P>
<P>
However, only the northern region will produce more flue cured
tobacco this year (2 million kilograms) than last year's 1.8
million kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Malawi is divided into three regions, namely southern, central
and northern regions.
</P>
<P>
As of July 2, Chapola said the average for burley at the
auction floors was 129 U.S. cents per kilogram while last year's
average price during the same period was 168 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Flue cured tobacco fetched 158 U.S. cents per kilogram as of
July 2 this year as compared to 180 cents in the same period in
1997. Due to the same dismal pricing, there has been an outcry
by many farmers especially small-scale producers who feel cheated
and would reap nothing in terms of profits as every cent realized
would go to payment of input loans.
</P>
<P>
Another contributing factor to the poor prices, according to
Chapola, is that much of the tobacco was damaged by the heavy
rains in the 1997/98 growing season.
</P>
<P>
"This also affected the quality of crop," lamented the tobacco
chief.
</P>
<P>
Some economic analysts feel it is high time Malawi shifted its
total dependence on tobacco for foreign exchange to other equally
profiting ventures especially in view of the escalating
anti-tobacco lobby internationally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandans Urged to Help Abducted Children Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The World Vision Uganda, a
non-governmental organization, is trying to bring the abducted
children in north Uganda to limelight and has appealed to
Ugandans and the world community to help the traumatized young
people.
</P>
<P>
Kofi Hagan, the country director of World Vision Uganda, told
a press conference here Thursday afternoon that his organization
has two centers in north Uganda whose duties are to help restore
hope in the children of reuniting with their communities.
</P>
<P>
He said some 4,000 to 6,000 children ranging from 10 to 20
years of age have been abducted by the rebels of the Lord's
Resistance Army since 1986.
</P>
<P>
Once abducted, the children would be forced to carry loads too
heavy for their backs, to be trained to kill and some of the
girls were given out to rebel commanders as rewards, he revealed.
</P>
<P>
Their center in Gulu district, set up in March 1995, has
offered skills training and psychological therapy to more than
3,500 children.
</P>
<P>
The center is facilitated by social workers, counselors,
health specialists, and vocational skills trainers.
</P>
<P>
"Many of them have lost so many years of education that it is
difficult for them to go back to school again and therefore
acquisition of basic skills prove very useful," he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
He called on all people to try to end the war in the country
so that people can be developed into productive force for the
society.
</P>
<P>
"Without the cessation of the war, there will be no end to the
abductions," he noted.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, a book named Restored Hope was issued to
all those present. It contains testimonies of 11 former abducted
children undergoing counseling in north Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
