<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Butros-Ghali: Superpowers Weakens U.N. Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Former United Nations Secretary
General Butros Butros-Ghali here Thursday accused "superpowers" of
having wielded too much influence which in effect made the world
body impotent to implement all its resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"Political reasons imposed by world superpowers are behind the
double standard policy of the U.N. in implementing some of its
resolutions," he said at a program organized by the U.N.
International Leadership Academy in Amman.
</P>
<P>
Some of the U.N.'s decisions were implemented while others are
not, he said. For example, the U.N. insists on implementing its
resolutions on Iraq, meanwhile such insistency has never been
exerted on the decision related to Israel's withdrawal from
southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"This confirms the superpowers' influence on the organization
whether the world body itself is serious in implementing its
decisions or not," he added.
</P>
<P>
Instead of naming the "superpowers," Butros-Ghali "There is
major dependence on the United States to resolve the Middle East
crisis and the European role will not be decisive but rather a
supporter to that of the U.S.."
</P>
<P>
The former U.N. chief noted that the current situation in the
U.N. is harming its image and damaging its function. "Many
countries no longer believe in the role of the world body and that
is why they are lukewarm to meet their financial obligations," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Butros-Ghali, who had been an Egyptian politician before
becoming U.N. chief in 1992 for a four-year tenure, is now
secretary general of the Francophonie. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
