<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Launches New Director-General Nomination Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The World Trade Organization (WTO)
has formally launched the process for the nomination of its next
director-general, said a WTO spokesman here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The incumbent WTO chief Renato Ruggiero has said in a letter to
the General Council that he intends to leave office not later than
April 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The WTO members, which wish to nominate candidates for the
position of the WTO director-general, should submit the names to
the chairman of the General Council by October 1 at the latest,
WTO spokesman Keith Rockwell told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The new director-general will be selected from the candidates
by consensus by the end of November and will be confirmed at the
December meeting of the General Council.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to emphasize that members will appoint the new
director-general on the basis of consensus," said John Weekes,
chairman of the General Council at its Wednesday meeting.
</P>
<P>
"I would urge members to bear this important reality in mind
over the coming months," Weekes said. "We are not planning an
election campaign; there will be no vote. We need to operate in a
way which will facilitate consensus, rather than make it more
difficult."
</P>
<P>
No formal nominations have been submitted yet but trade sources
say that there are at least five potential candidates. They are
Brazil's foreign minister Felipe Luiz Lampreia, former Canadian
trade minister Roy MacLaren, former Moroccan trade minister Hassan
Abouyoub, former New Zealand premier Mike Moore, and Thai deputy
prime minister Supachai Panitchpakdi.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
