<HEADLINE> NATO Chief to Visit Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana is to discuss the Kosovo crisis and a crisis-related joint
military exercise in Macedonia during his planned trip to the
Balkan country next week, it was learned here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, aimed at demonstrating NATO's concern and ability
to deploy in the region rapidly, will be held between September 12
and 18 with the codename "Cooperative Best Effort".
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 troops from some 20 NATO and Partnership for
Peace member countries will take part in the Macedonia military
exercise.
</P>
<P>
Solana's visit to Macedonia was described by a NATO official,
who asked not to be named, as "politically more relevant".
</P>
<P>
During his trip, the NATO chief will examine the military
training center at Krivolak which NATO has planned to turn into a
base should the need arise for the western military alliance to
deploy what it has called preventive forces in the region.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia has offered the Krivolak center as a permanent
training center for the NATO's Partnership for Peace programs.
</P>
<P>
NATO also scheduled a military exercise for neighboring Albania
from August 17 to 22.
</P>
<P>
Both Macedonia and Albania are members of NATO's Partnership
for Peace program.
</P>
<P>
In mid June, NATO conducted an air-borne exercise in Albania as
a demonstration of the alliance's solidarity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
