<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- the European Investment Bank (EIB) will offer 56
million Tunisian dinars (48.2 million U.S. dollars) in loans to
the Tunisian Electricity And Gas Company under an agreement signed
recently in Brussels, the Arabic Al Sabah reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said with the money, the total amount of loans
extended by the EIB to Tunisia will reach 250 million Tunisian
dinars (215.5 million dollars) within the framework of
Euro-Mediterranean cooperation.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisia's trade with African states have reached 104
million dollars in 1997, up 14.3 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics released by the Tunisian Ministry of
Trade showed that Cote d'Ivoire was the biggest consumer of
Tunisian goods, accounting for 16.5 percent Tunisia's total
exports to African states.
</P>
<P>
And 30 percent of the Tunisian imports are from the African
continent, the statistics said.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's revenues from taxation on property deals
reached 14.88 million U.S. dollars in June, rising by 6.7 percent
than that of the same month of last year, according to the
Ministry of Finance figures released this week.
</P>
<P>
Collected property tax revenues for the first six months this
year rose by 13.81 percent than that of the same period of last
year, standing at 80.58 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
