<HEADLINE> Whisky Has to Contain At Least 40 Pct of Alcohol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Any alcoholic beverage that
contains less than 40 percent of alcohol but has been sold with
the label of whisky may no longer continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
The European Court of Justice ruled on Thursday that such
alcoholic beverage with less than 40 percent alcohol content is
not eligible for the label of whisky any more.
</P>
<P>
The court made the ruling after the Scottish Whisky Association
made repeated complaints about the diluted whiskies made and sold
by French, Canadian and American producers in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The court ruled that the brand "Gold River" can from now on be
sold as either alcoholic beverage or spirit but no longer labelled
as whisky.
The Gold River contains only 30 percent of alcohol. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
