<HEADLINE> NATO Subregional Headquarters in Greece to Begin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- A subregional headquarters of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) in Larissa, central
Greece, will begin operation on October 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Greece's first army corps leadership announced Thursday that
the headquarters in the Greek town of Tyrnavos would have about
600 Greek and foreign staff with the annually budget of operation
amounting to 25 billion drachmas (about 833 million U.S. dollars),
the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The Greek army officials said that the establishment of the
NATO headquarters had both strategic and economic importance for
the wider Larissa region.
</P>
<P>
They also stressed that national sovereignty and defense
remained an inalienable and sovereign rights of Greece as there
was no correlation with the new NATO headquarters.
</P>
<P>
While in times of crisis and operations, the region of
operational control would be set out by NATO in cooperation with
the Greek government, which had the first say on matters of
national defense, they said.
</P>
<P>
Under NATO's new structure, the number of NATO's regional
headquarters was reduced from 65 to 20, with strategic regional
and subregional commands.
</P>
<P>
In the southern flank, NATO, with a regional headquarters in
Naples, Italy, has four subregional headquarters in Madrid,
Verona, Izmir and Larissa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mauritian Finance Minister Visits Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Mauritian Finance Minister Kumar
Bunwaree arrived here Thursday for a three-day visit in
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at the Maputo airport upon his arrival, Bunwaree
said the relations between Mozambique and his country has been
increasingly strengthened with very good cooperations.
</P>
<P>
Mauritius has just taken up a series of measures to encourage
its countrymen to invest in Mozambique, he said.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, the minister will discuss with Mozambican
entrepreneurs and the authorities concerned on bilateral
cooperations in agriculture, fisheries and industry, especially
among small and medium scaled enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Bunwaree revealed that he will also consult with the
Mozambican side on establishing more convenient air transport
between the two countries, for "We hope the bilateral relations
would be developed faster," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mauritius is especially interested in developing a special
economic zone in the Zambeze Valley in central Mozambique, he
said, adding that the program will involve a land area of 100,000
hectares and the development projects include social facilities
such as road and housing.
</P>
<P>
The minister is scheduled to visit two sugar plants in
Marromey region in central Mozambique's Sofala Province, which
Mauritius plans to invest in the rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
According to Mozambique News Agency, the Mauritian minister
paid a courtesy call on Mozambican Prime Minister Pascoal Mocumbi
Thursday afternoon and discussed investment related issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Plans to Extend Helms-Burton Waiver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton has
planned to sign papers authorizing a renewal of the waiver for
another six months of the Helms-Burton law that requires the
United States to penalize foreign firms investing in Cuba, the
White House said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Mike McCurry said Clinton would sign the papers
later on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It will be the second time that Clinton is going to waive the
sanctions since he signed the legislation into law in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Helms-Burton law has enraged U.S. allies in Europe and
Canada. they accused Washington of pursuing extraterritoriality
by penalizing foreign companies that invest in Cuban property
seized after the 1959 Cuban revolution and vowed to retaliate if
the United States enforce the law against their companies
investing in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Even Clinton has complained about the rigid law despite the
fact that he has signed it, saying it constrained his ability to
conduct foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
The ground work for the latest waiver came in an agreement
reached in May between U.S. and European negotiators. The
European Union agreed to adopt certain "disciplines" to inhibit
and deter investments by its businessmen in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Clinton himself has worked to improve some contacts with
Cuba, allowing Cuban families in America to send more money back
home to relatives and easing restrictions on charter flights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Constantinescu Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
held talks with visiting Romanian President Emil Constantinescu
and said the Balkan nation is making impressive progress.
</P>
<P>
"The progress this nation is making is very impressive and
they are very important to our future," Clinton told reporters
after his meeting with Constantinescu in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
Constantinescu said that he and Clinton discussed the
economic dimension of the strategic partnership between the
United States and Romania. He said investments by American
companies "can help Romania develop a computerized society based
on high technology" to "face the challenges of the third
millennium."
</P>
<P>
The Romanian president is here seeking support for his
country to join NATO. He stressed that the Balkan nation is
important to the stability of southern Europe.
</P>
<P>
He told Clinton that Romania is trying to live up to the
slogan: "Be positive" the NATO membership.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, although he supports expansion of NATO, gave no
concrete assurances of specific date for Romania to enter.
</P>
</TEXT>
