<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Hardline Minister Makes Surprise Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Former hardline Interior Minister
Charles Pasqua Thursday made surprise remarks on immigration, one of
the most sensitive issues in the country, by suggesting that all
illegal immigrants be given residency in France.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the daily Le Monde, Pasqua, who was the
designer of the 1993 conservative immigration law which virtually
closed door to immigrants, said that when France is strong as it is
now, it should be generous to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
"One cannot go out unless regularizing all the people who ask
for it, except those who have committed another offense," he said.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the government for holding a paradoxical attitude
toward immigration, as it has failed to tackle the problem of
immigration while claiming that France is capable of integrating
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Pasqua, who is a senator from the Gaullist Rally for the Republic
(RPR), also suggested that France continue to have full control over
its frontiers instead of handing over the power to the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
"Control, that is to say not to let Brussels decide on behalf of
us, as the Amsterdam treaty predicts. That also implies negotiating
with the countries of origin (of immigrants)," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Amsterdam Treaty calls for the opening of frontiers between
the European Union countries to allow free circulation of people.
</P>
<P>
He relaunched his idea for establishing a quota system of
admitting immigrants from the former colonies of France, giving them
priority in immigrant's status.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Continued War Mars Image of Uganda: Dutch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Charge D'Affaires of Dutch
Embassy to Uganda Mrs Saskia de Lang said here Thursday afternoon
that the continued rebel war in north Uganda has marred the image
of Uganda abroad and hampered its development.
</P>
<P>
She made these remarks when launching a book Restored Hope by
Robby Muhumuza of the World Vision, a non-governmental
organization which mainly focuses its attention in Uganda on
checking the spread of AIDS and detraumatizing the former
abducted young people in the north.
</P>
<P>
The book contains testimonies of 11 former abducted children
undergoing counseling in humanitarian centers in the norther part
of this east African country.
</P>
<P>
The war there and the abductions have affected Uganda's
attractiveness to foreign investors and put a strain on the
social resources which would otherwise have been useful to the
country, the Dutch diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
The continued and rising insecurity in the region is hampering
the development of Uganda because it scares investors away, she
added.
</P>
<P>
Since 1986, some 4,000 to 6,000 children of 10 to 20 years of
age have been abducted by the rebels of the Lord Resistance Army.
They have been forced to kill and damage.
</P>
<P>
She pledged that her government will continue to provide
various kinds of help to the World Vision.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Netherlands contributed a total of 35,000 U.S.
Dollars to boost the development of Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Chief Responds to U.S. Proposal for More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Head of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) Renato Ruggiero has promised that his
organization will make every effort to improve the public
understanding of its role, said his spokesman Keith Rockwell here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a speech on Wednesday responding to the United States'
proposal to increase the organization's transparency, Ruggiero
urged the General Council of the WTO to do more to promote
transparency and dispel the misleading impression of secrecy.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that no real progress will be made to improve the
exchange of information about the nature and goals of the WTO
unless there is a strong commitment from the governments of its
members.
</P>
<P>
In a proposal to the WTO General Council Wednesday, the United
States complained that the minutes of General Council meetings
generally come out only a month after the events, and even then
they are marked "restricted" and may remain unavailable to the
press and general public for as long as six months.
</P>
<P>
The same problem exists with panel reports, leading to
different interpretations by interested parties who would claim
victory by quoting parts of the reports, said Ms Rita Hayes, U.S.
permanent representative to the WTO,
</P>
<P>
She hoped that the General Council will move to adopt the U.S.
proposal immediately.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
