<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Economic Growth Projected to Slow to 2.5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- World economic growth is
expected to slow to 2.5 percent in 1998 after two straight years
of over 3 percent, the United Nations said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The after-effects of the Asian financial crisis has plunged
several of the fastest growing economies into a severe recession,
and highlighted dangerous weaknesses in the international market
for financial assets, said the 1998 edition of the U.N. World
Economic and Social Survey.
</P>
<P>
It said the forecast "is surrounded with an unusual degree of
uncertainty" as there is volatility in financial markets, coupled
with the slowdown in world trade and continued difficulties of
nations in defending their own currencies.
</P>
<P>
It said the developing countries are hardest hit in the crisis
and their growth this year might not exceed 3 percent after an
average of 5 percent or better in five of the six preceding years.
</P>
<P>
The industrialized economies are projected to grow by 2.25
percent, down from a decade-high of 2.7 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The economies in transition, which are emerging from severe
economic contraction in 1990-1996, are expected to grow by 3
percent or more this year, after 2.7 percent growth in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Despite the economic difficulties in Asia, world trade is
forecast to grow about 7 percent down from an estimated 9 percent
in 1997 when a total of about 5.5 trillion U.S. dollars in
merchandise trade was reached, the survey said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
