<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM to Visit Northern Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz will visit northern Cyprus next Monday to show Turkey's
support to the Turkish Cypriots who set up a breakaway republic
there.
</P>
<P>
During the one-day visit, Yilmaz will participate in a
celebration ceremony marking the 24th anniversary of Turkey's
military intervention in Cyprus and meet with Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash, Turkey's Anatolia News Agency reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz is also expected to discuss with Turkish Cypriot
officials the latest tension between the Greek and Turkish
communities in Cyprus, especially the Cypriot government's plan to
deploy Russian-made S-300 missiles on the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops landed and took over the northern third of the island in
response to a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared in 1983 the "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" which was only recognized by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
At present, around 35,000-strong Turkish troops are stationed
in northern Cyprus with a claimed aim to protect Turkish
Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
