<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pan-African Environment Conference to Open in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Environment ministers from 53
African states will meet in Mozambique's capital Maputo from July
protection, the U.N. Environment Program (UNEP) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the ministers' gathering, a series of workshops
attended by experts from all over Africa will be held on concrete
issues concerned between July 18 and 22, said the Nairobi-based
UNEP in a newsletter.
</P>
<P>
The Pan-African Conference on Sustainable Integrated Coastal
Management (PACSICOM) will provide a unique chance for the
continent to boost inter-governmental dialog on the rising
threats to the marine and coastal environment, UNEP claimed.
</P>
<P>
The ministers are expected to jointly issue resolutions, the
PACSICOM Statement, and the Maputo Declaration at the end of the
meeting to meet the complex challenges Africa is facing on
coastal management, according to the UNEP newsletter.
</P>
<P>
"The regional response to the environmental challenges facing
the African continent cannot be piecemeal. It must be conceived
and acted upon in an integrated and systematic way," said Klaus
Topfer, UNEP's Executive Director.
</P>
<P>
"PACSICOM brings together the combined political, scientific
and technical strength of Africa on matters relating to the state
of the continent's marine and coastal environment. This is a
unique opportunity for joint action," he said in the newsletter.
</P>
<P>
The conference comes at a time when global attention is being
especially paid to the marine environment throughout this year,
the Year of Ocean declared by the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is co-sponsored by the governments of Mozambique
and Finland, UNEP, as well as the U.N. Educational, Scientific
and Cultural Organization (UNESCO). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
