<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African Customs Union Finalizing Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Southern African Customs
Union (SACU) countries are finalizing their trade offer to the
larger Southern African Development Community (SADC) grouping as
the region moves toward setting up a single, stronger trade body.
</P>
<P>
So far, Namibia, Botswana and Lesotho have submitted lists of
"sensitive" products on which protection may be sought while
South Africa is still fine-tuning its list, South African Press
Association quoted a Namibian newspaper as saying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Namibia, Botswana, Lesotho, Swaziland and South Africa make up
SACU and they also belong to 14-member SADC.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's provisional list of sensitive products included
fish, wines, spirits and red meat. Beef was understood to have
featured prominently on the lists of the sensitive products
already submitted by Namibia and others.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from all the five SACU member countries were
scheduled to meet at the weekend to clarify their joint trade
offer to SADC.
</P>
<P>
It is now envisaged that a SADC trade protocol will be fully
ratified before the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is reported to have expressed willingness to make
tariff reductions in an effort to facilitate the creation of a
regional free trade area.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of a regional free trade area would threaten
the existence of SACU whose renegotiation has been on the drawing
board for the past four years.
</P>
<P>
The customs union's existence had also been threatened by
negotiations between South Africa and the European Union (EU) and
in particular by recent revelations that South Africa expressed
its willingness to tentatively remove barriers on a larger
percentage of EU imports coming into the country, a move feared
to hurt producers from the entire SACU.
</P>
<P>
SACU members draw a large portion of their total revenue from
the customs union pool. Over 30 percent of Namibia's annual
revenue is derived from the regional revenue pool. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Not Possible in Middle East without Syria: Chirac </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
Thursday defended Syria's place in the political geography of the
Middle East, claiming that peace is not possible in the region
without the involvement of Syria.
</P>
<P>
At a state dinner held at the Elysee presidential palace in
honor of Syrian President Hafez al-Assad, Chirac also pleaded for
a "united and free Lebanon which has sovereignty over all its
territory."
</P>
<P>
Lebanon is being occupied by the Israeli troops in its south
and is hosting 30,000 Syrian troops who are there in the name of
protecting the country against Israeli aggression.
</P>
<P>
Chirac vowed to work together with Syria for "a just, global
and lasting peace" in the Middle East, whose present situation he
described as being "close to complete deadlock."
</P>
<P>
He also called on Israel to return the Golan Heights -- annexed
by Israel but claimed by Syria -- to Syrian sovereignty, and said
that the principle of land for peace is the basis of the French
position for a long time.
</P>
<P>
"Peace for land with the return of Golan to Syria. Peace for
land with the pursuit of the Israeli redeployment and the
transfers of power in the Palestinian territories, in conformity
with the agreements signed," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
He said that Lebanon is "dear" to France, which he said wants
to see Lebanon go ahead on the way of "reconciliation,
reconstruction, democracy and liberty."
</P>
<P>
Chirac also said that Israel should be entitled to "full and
entire" security, maintain its internationally recognized
frontiers, and enjoy peaceful relations with its neighbors once it
has returned the conquered Arab territories.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Orders Probe of Behest Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
said here Thursday that he has ordered Finance Secretary Edgardo
Espiritu to submit all the documents pertaining to alleged behest
loans incurred during the Fidel Ramos administration.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said Espiritu was set to submit to the Presidential
Palace the loan records, adding that his government would make
appropriate conclusions after the documents are examined.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Espiritu reported to Estrada that big corporations
well connected with former president Ramos were able to avail of
loans from the Development Bank of the Philippines which were
supposedly intended for small and medium-scale enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Finance has started investigating the alleged
behest loans and unliquidated cash advances amounting to billions
of pesos to Ramos' "cronies".
</P>
<P>
Because of the bank records uncovered by Espiritu, Estrada
ordered a thorough audit of financial statements and other bank
records of government financial institutions to detect possible
misuse of public funds.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said that
the audit shall also cover a review of all transactions by
government financial institutions and government-owned or
controlled corporations during the Ramos administration.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said he and Espiritu believed that the loans should have
been extended to small and medium-scale enterprises to encourage
investments in the countryside and balance the economic
development of the country.
</P>
<P>
Zamora explained that the questionable loans were uncovered in
the course of the review being done by the Department of Finance
on the country's true financial state, in preparation for the
drafting of the 1999 national budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Makes Headway in Reforms: U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rubin said the Mozambican government has done tremendous work,
and that he would bring this message back to the United States to
the private sectors, the corner stone for economic development.
</P>
<P>
After talks with his Mozambican counterpart Tomaz Salomao,
Rubin said that American entrepreneurs have always shown
interests in doing business in the country.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government would advice the World Bank to have a
pioneering program for creating an atmosphere for foreign
investment, Rubin said in a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. treasury secretary said one of the topics of
his talks with the Mozambican officials is the efficiency of
the country's judicial departments, noting that the judicial
officials need more training.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Minister called on Mozambican Premier Pascoal Mocumbi
for talks, met local businessmen and toured a primary school
after arriving here Wednesday. He left here later Thursday for
Kenya, the last leg of his five-nation African tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
