<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Need for Coordinated Relief Efforts in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Economic and
Social Council Thursday held a panel discussion on natural
disasters with United Nations resident and humanitarian
coordinators.
</P>
<P>
Speakers cited lessons learned form Afghanistan earthquakes,
forest fires in Indonesia and EL Nino floods in Peru to emphasize
the coordinated relief efforts in natural disaster situations.
</P>
<P>
Lack of preparedness and coordination could contribute to the
human toll in a natural catastrophe, United Nations Humanitarian
Coordinator for Afghanistan Alfred Witschi-Cestari said.
</P>
<P>
If the international community was not prepared for a natural
event, there would be a human drama, he said, adding that in
Afghanistan, the international community had to overcome
tremendous difficulties in order to reach the affected population,
but coordination had been established almost immediately after the
facts were made clear.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Resident Coordinator for Indonesia Ravi Rajan
described the emergency response to the extensive forest fires
that burned in the country in the past year.
</P>
<P>
He said the support of the government and the international
community facilitated the effective coordination of the response
to the disaster.
</P>
<P>
Yet, he said, the scope and extent of the disaster was such
that the combined efforts of all actors were not adequate to deal
with it fully, and vulnerability to such disasters would only
increase in the future and thus the elaboration of prevention and
preparedness strategies were necessary.
</P>
<P>
Addressing recent floods in Peru, the country's United Nations
Resident Coordinator Kim Bolduc, said that the 1997-1998
phenomenon was considered as a El Nino.
</P>
<P>
He said El Nino was a typical natural disaster due to its four
to six months' duration, and other natural disasters tended to be
violent, but shorter in length.
</P>
<P>
He said that in preparation for its arrival, the Peruvian
government had started prevention activities in early 1997, but
the country still suffered enormous losses, and 600,000 people
were directly affected, and future El Nino would be stronger and
more devastating each time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
