<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Reaffirms Support for Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Greek President Costis
Stephanopoulos Friday reiterated Greece's support for Cyprus in
efforts to find a just, viable and feasible solution to the
problems of the island republic which has been divided since 1974.
</P>
<P>
In a message on the 24th anniversary of the Turkish invasion
and occupation of one-third of Cyprus, Stephanopoulos said that it
was their duty to support these efforts which would also be a
tribute to the memory of all those who gave up their lives for the
independence and unity of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since July 1974 when Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the island
in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are about 35,000 Turkish troops stationed in
northern Cyprus which declared its independence in 1983 but was
recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Greek president urged Turkey to withdraw its troops from
northern Cyprus so that "all Cypriots, irrespective of ethnic
origin or religion, can march together down the road of
conciliation and creation, within the framework of a bizonal,
bicommunal federation."
</P>
<P>
Stephanopoulos added that it would open a new page in the
centuries-long peaceful co-existence of the two communities in
Cyprus.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
