<HEADLINE> FIFA Orders FAZ to Pay Former Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- FIFA has insisted on its earlier
decision that the Football Association of Zambia (FAZ) must pay
its former national coach Burkhard Ziese 127,945.70 U.S. Dollars
within 30 days for breach of contract.
</P>
<P>
FIFA made the ruling last week after throwing out an appeal
lodged by FAZ contesting an earlier FIFA decision to compensate
Ziese, said James Mazumba, FAZ's general secretary on Thursday,
the Times of Zambia reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
FIFA said FAZ's appeal was lodged in a few days late and
therefor could not be heard.
</P>
<P>
The world soccer body stated that a match defeat is not
sufficient ground to dismiss a coach and that FAZ is liable for
payment of the sum of money claimed by Ziese within the period of
30 days.
</P>
<P>
Ziese, a German-born soccer coach, was fired after Zambian was
routed 0-4 by Egypt in the Cup of Africa Nations finals last
February in Burkina Fasso.
</P>
<P>
He was sacked four months after signing a two-year contract
with FAZ on December 20, 1997 at a salary of 15,000 Dollars per
month. Under the contact, he is entitled to six months' salary if
his services are terminated by FAZ.
</P>
<P>
In a letter written to FIFA after his dismissal, besides the
compensation, Ziese also claimed a refund of 37,945.70 dollars
which he spent on the national team when they camped in Gambia
preparing for the CAN matches, bringing the total to 127,945.70
Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
