<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore PM Defends Government Economic Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong Friday urged companies not to pin their hopes on the
government to salvage them out of the current economic
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a dinner Friday evening to mark the 30th
anniversary of the Development Bank of Singapore, one of the four
biggest banks in the island-country, Goh said the market must be
the driving force rather than the government.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his agreement with a recent research report that
says the government "can ease the pain as the economy contracts
but it can not stop the contraction in any meaningful way."
</P>
<P>
"when faced with an external shock, the correct policy is to
allow prices and asset-values to adjust to the new realities," he
said, adding that Singapore's problem is a fall in regional demand
and a slowing of the electronic cycle in the U.S..
</P>
<P>
"Both of which we can do nothing about," he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister was responding to some complaints by some
businessmen over government inactiveness to cope with the current
economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
Some businessmen have expressed disappointment at the
2-billion-Singapore-dollar package measures announced by the
government at the end of June to boost the downturning economy.
</P>
<P>
They complained that nothing was being done to stimulate demand
and urged the government to act now to arrest the decline in
economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
Some others urged the government to pay more attention to the
property market and suggested that government-linked companies
soak up the excess supply in the property market.
</P>
<P>
Goh said "businessmen should know that unwarranted negative
reaction to the government's management of the economic crisis
without offering any serious suggestions to overcome the crisis is
like biting one's own tail."
</P>
<P>
"Being critical without sound basis, not only do they confuse
the public, they also affect the psychology of the population and
undermine market confidence in the very measures designed to help
them weather the crisis," the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said anyone who suggests that the government-linked
companies go in to prop up the market by paying more than what the
properties are worth is asking the government to bail them out.
</P>
<P>
The government will not do that, either directly or indirectly
through the government-linked companies, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He asked the businessmen to have faith in the government
leadership in tackling the challenges created by the regional
crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Lauds Economic Cooperation With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait and China enjoy mutually
beneficial economies and vast potential for economic cooperation,
according to Abdulmohsen Al-Jeaan, ambassador of the State of
Kuwait to China.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said today that an open Kuwaiti market provides
an ideal point for absorbing China's high quality and high-tech
products. He added that China's constantly improved investment
environment will become even more attractive to Kuwaiti investors
</P>
<P>
Jeaan pointed out two types of economic cooperation between
Kuwait and China. He cited the first as the development assistance
projects signed between the two governments. For example, Kuwait
has provided soft loans totalling 10 miilion Dinars (34 million US
dollars) for the Integrated Rural Development Project in Northwest
China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, the largest Sino-Kuwaiti
project of its type to date.
</P>
<P>
He pointed to the second form of economic cooperation as
investment projects and noted that the Kuwaiti government
encourages businessmen to invest in China. For example, Kuwaiti
businessmen have invested in 22 projects in China since August
1982, with total investments standing at 152.3 million Dinars,
according to the ambassador.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China has also contracted a number of
construction projects in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The foreign trade volume between the two countries for the
first five months of this year stood at 101 million US dollars, up
29 percent on the previous year's period, according to the Kuwaiti
embassy. China's export to Kuwait stood at 48.4 million US
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
