<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Israeli-Palestinian Meeting Due Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai will meet senior Palestinian official Mahmoud Abbas (Abu
Mazen) Sunday in Tel Aviv to resume direct talks, Israel Radio
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) refused to confirm
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli Defense Ministry spokesman confirmed that the
meeting was agreed upon in the wake of contacts between Israel,
the United States and the PNA.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the PNA has rejected Israel's request that
PNA President Yasser Arafat meet with Mordechai. But Israeli
sources were quoted as saying that Abu Mazen, Arafat's deputy, has
the power to take decisions on behalf of Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat, however, refused to
confirm the reported meeting, saying that it would be decided
only at the PNA Cabinet meeting this weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Mordechai-Mazen meeting was believed to be the result of
the intervenation by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
who said no progress in reviving the stalled peace process would
be possible without direct talks.
</P>
<P>
Albright's call for direct talks came after the U.S. had failed
to persuade Israel to accept its proposal for a 13.1 percent
Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Washington has become increasingly impatient with the
protracted deadlock in the peace talks which broke down 16 months
ago when Israel began building a Jewish settlement in the Arab
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai has reportedly been authorized by Israel's powerful
Inner Cabinet to limit his talks on only two issues -- the
cancellation of the clauses in the Palestinian Covenant calling
for Israel's destruction and the scope of the Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
As far as the withdrawal was concerned, Mordechai was asked
to discuss the nature of the newly-proposed Area D, which is among
the 13.1 percent areas due to be handed over to the PNA.
</P>
<P>
According to Israel's plan, the Israeli army would retain the
right to re-enter Area D for security reasons after the withdrawal
and the Palestinians would also be barred from building in such
areas.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the PNA is completely controlling 3 percent of the
West Bank, called Area A, and sharing control with Israel over 24
percent of West Bank, called Area B. But Israel retains control
over the rest of the West Bank, or 70 percent, which was
designated as Area C.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has reiterated that the 13.1 percent withdrawal should
come from Area C, and this scope would never be renegotiated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Attacks "Separatist" Party in Scotland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
on Friday attacked the Scottish National Party (SNP).
</P>
<P>
Awaring rising tendency of independence in Scotland, Blair
flied to Edingburge on Friday for a one-day visit to drum up
support for Labor Party's management in the area.
</P>
<P>
A recent poll put the SNP 14 percentage points ahead of Labor
in voting intentions for the new Edinburgh parliament.
</P>
<P>
It was in stark contrast to polls conducted across Britain
which give Labor a massive lead of over 20 points over the
opposition Conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Speaking ahead of meeting potential Labor candidates for next
year's Scottish parliamentary elections, Blair predicted that SNP
support would fall before voters go to the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
It was "absurd" that Scotland's interests would be served by
becoming independent, Blair told reporters in the Scottish
capital.
</P>
<P>
The SNP's strong showing in recent polls has raised the
question whether Labor can retain its dominance in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
The government is setting up parliaments in Edinburgh and
Cardiff so that the people of Scotland and Wales can run their own
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The SNP says that if it emerges as the largest party in the new
129-seat Edinburgh Parliament, it will insist on a referendum on
independence within the first four-year term.
</P>
<P>
According to the polls, a plebiscite could result in a majority
in favor of breaking the link with England which dated from 1707.
</P>
</TEXT>
