<HEADLINE> Taihu Lake Witnesses Improved Water Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The water quality in east China's
Taihu Lake has improved significantly during the first half of
this year, according to information released during today's
conference on pollution control in the area.
</P>
<P>
The achievements can be attributed to a two-year local
government effort to increase rainfall, according to Xie Zhenhua,
director of the State Environmental Protection Administration.
</P>
<P>
However, Xie noted that the status quo continues to lag far
behind demands of the State Council, and great difficulty remains
in overcoming related problems and ensuring that all sources of
pollution in the area meet emission standards by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
"We must not relax our efforts," said Xie.
</P>
<P>
Some 670-odd small plants creating serious pollution in the
Taihu Lake area have been forced to close since 1996, with 42.1
percent, or over 1,000 major polluters in the region, fulfilling
emission standards by the end of June 1998.
</P>
<P>
Five new urban sewage treatment plants have a total daily
handling capacity of 580,000 tons of wastewater, and a sixth plant
is under construction.
</P>
<P>
Local governments have also expanded efforts to control
silting, dredge rivers, protecting drinking water resources and
control fish farming and shipping-related pollution in the area.
</P>
<P>
The Taihu Lake region, one of China's most developed regions,
covers 36,000 sq.km in Jiangsu and Zhejiang provinces and
Shanghai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
