<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Buries Remains of Last Tsar, Dependants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Friday buried the remains
of its last tsar and his dependants, exactly 80 years after they
were executed by Bolsheviks.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and his wife Naina, both dressed in black, attended the
service at Peter and Paul Cathedral in St. Petersburg, the former
imperial capital.
</P>
<P>
Upon Yeltsin's announcement on Thursday that he would join the
ceremony, Communist deputies condemned his decision, saying the
tsar was a brutal autocrat and that the president's attendance
would divide society.
</P>
<P>
As clergy from the Russian Orthodox church sang a mournful
dirge and bells rang, workers lowered the coffins holding the
royal bones into crypts in the church.
</P>
<P>
The nine small coffins contained the bones of Nicholas II, his
wife, three of their children, three servants and the family
doctor.
</P>
<P>
In February, a government commission ruled after seven years of
research that the remains, found in 1991 near the city of
Yekaterinburg, where the royal family members were executed,
belonged to Nicholas and his family.
</P>
<P>
The government decided that the remains should be reburied in
Peter and Paul Cathedral, the resting place of Russian emperors
since Peter the Great, who died in 1725.
</P>
<P>
DNA tests conducted in Russia and abroad confirmed the identity
of the remains to a 99.9 percent degree of certainty but the
Orthodox Church Abroad, which split off after the revolution,
claims the real remains are in a church in Belgium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four South Asian Countries Reaffirm Sub-Regional  Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Foreign secretaries of
Bangladesh, Bhutan, India and Nepal reaffirmed here Friday their
commitment to pursuing sub-regional economic cooperation to
accelerate economic growth, overcome infrastructure constraints
and develop and make the optimal use of complementarities.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretaries are meeting here for the second time to
consider the working modalities of the sub-regional Growth
Quadrangle, initiated by Nepal in December 1996 with a view to
jointly developing the eastern Himalayan rivers for rapid economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
The Growth Quadrangle comprises Bangladesh, Bhutan, India and
Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretaries decided that the Growth Quadrangle will
be pursued within the framework of the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC) with the objective of complementing
and supplementing regional cooperation, the Nepali Foreign
Ministry said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
They reiterated their decision at the first meeting held here
in April last year and decided to assign Bhutan the coordinating
responsibilities in the area of environment, Bangladesh in the
area of optimal and sustainable utilization of natural resources
and energy, India trade and investment facilitation and promotion
and Nepal multimodal transportation and communication and tourism.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to constitute working groups to examine and
recommend specific projects for sub-regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In making proposals, the working groups will be guided by the
principles of maximum coordination and a building block approach.
</P>
<P>
And the proposals will be submitted to a steering committee
consisting of foreign secretaries of the four countries for
consideration, the Nepali Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretaries agreed that the meeting of the working
groups on sectoral areas would be held soon in order to give
further impetus to the objectives of the Growth Quadrangle, the
ministry added.
</P>
<P>
SAARC was formed in December 1985 to promote regional
cooperation in agreed areas among its member countries --
Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri
Lanka.
</P>
<P>
At the 9th summit held in May 1997 in the Maldives, SAARC
leaders encouraged the development of specific projects relevant
to the specific individual needs of three or more member
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
