<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The number of poor people in
Malaysia has increased from 8.9 percent to 9 percent of the
population since the economic crisis began last year, Malaysian
Rural Development Minister Annuar Musa said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that agencies under his ministry would be
reorganized to reduce the effects of the crisis especially on the
rural population.
</P>
<P>
"All poverty eradication programs and village industry projects
must be intensified," he said at a function in Malacca, some 145
kilometers south of here, according to the Malaysian national news
agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
He said his ministry would also come up with an action plan,
based on a national action plan, to help the rural folks overcome
the effects of the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Under the action plan, infrastructure projects such as village
roads and water supply systems and complaints from smallholders
would be dealt with quickly, he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has a population of more than 21 million. 
