<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
would pursue the peace initiatives of the previous administration
to try to forge a settlement with all rebel forces, Executive
Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said he is submitting to Estrada next week a list of
members of several government peace panels which would start peace
talks with the New People's Army (NPA), the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) and the extremists group, the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
"There is no question that the Estrada administration is
determined to pursue the peace process and we will begin the talks
possibly within a few weeks," Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
NPA and MILF had been engaged in peace talks with the
government during the past few years, but the talks made little
progress in reaching any peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
In September 1996, the Moro National Liberation Front, the
largest rebel group in the country, signed a final peace pact with
the Fidel Ramos administration.
</P>
<P>
Estrada assumed the presidency on June 30 this year. Because of
the presidential elections in May and the change of government in
June, the government's peace talks with the rebel groups were
suspended. 
</P>
