<HEADLINE> Worldnet Dialogue on Intellectual Property Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts, senior U.S. trade
official and representatives from leading world IPR organizations
today joined in a live interactive Worldnet dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the State Copyright Bureau and the State
Intellectual Property Rights Office discussed issues concerning
IPR protection with Joseph Papovich, Assistant Trade
Representative of the U.S. Trade Representative Office, and Steven
Metalitz, Vice President of the International Intellectual
Property Alliance (IIPA).
</P>
<P>
Papovich and Metalitz explained specific policies and
regulations during the one-hour informal dialogue, the first of
its kind ever held between the various parties.
</P>
<P>
"Dialogue on IPR protection will be highly beneficial to both
China and the United States," according to Chinese representative
Li Mingde
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR) also participated in the event and tabled questions
concerning copyright piracy.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR government initiated an extensive campaign against
copyright piracy, with related efforts in 1997 leading to the
confiscation of 4.5 million pirated compact discs. Statistics
shows that an additional 2.5 million pirated discs were seized in
the first three months this year.
</P>
<P>
The World Intellectual Property Organization held its 1998
Asian Regional Conference in Hong Kong in June. 
</P>
