<HEADLINE> US Trade Deficit Shoots Up to Record High in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. trade deficit climbed
up to a record high of 15.75 billion U.S. dollars in May as the
lingering economic crisis in Asia brought U.S. exports down to the
lowest level in 15 months, the Commerce Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit for May was 10.3 percent higher than the
April imbalance of 14.27 billion dollars, indicating that the
fallout from Asia's currency crisis will be more severe for the
U.S. manufacturers and farmers than previous forecast.
</P>
<P>
For the first five months this year, the trade deficit is
running at a record annual rate of 156 billion dollars, 42 percent
higher than last year.
</P>
<P>
For May, the deficit with Japan narrowed by 8.5 percent to 4.95
billion dollars, the smallest imbalance since January. But for
the year, the deficit with Japan is running 18 percent above the
same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The deficit with newly industrialized countries in Asia, a
category that includes South Korea and other nations hard-hit by
the region's economic turmoil, totals 8 billion dollars for the
first five months this year, nearly a 20-fold increase from the
same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. deficit with the 15-nation European Union slipped to
1.67 billion dollars in May, down 49 percent from the April
deficit as imports of European cars and chemical products fell.
</P>
<P>
But the deficit with Mexico rose by 19 percent to 1.52 billion
dollars, the largest gap in a year.
</P>
<P>
The inflating deficit in May reflected a 1.2 percent drop in
U.S. exports of goods and services, which fell to 76.23 billion
dollars, the lowest level in 15 months.
</P>
<P>
Exports of the U.S. farm products declined by 113 million
dollars to 3.65 billion dollars, the lowest level since September
1994. Exports of telecommunications equipment fell 275 million
dollars to 1.89 billion dollars while exports of U.S. autos and
auto parts dropped 488 million dollars to 5.98 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's imports in May went up 0.5 percent to
91.98 billion dollars, the second highest level on record.
Imports of computers and computer parts rose 289 million dollars
to 5.6 billion dollars while imports of foreign cars and auto
parts were up 353 million dollars to 12.5 billion dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
