<HEADLINE> WTO Chief Enveils Plan for Enhanced Cooperation With NGOs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Head of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) Renato Ruggiero announced here Friday a plan to
enhance his organization's cooperation with non-governmental
organizations (NGOs) in response to the United States' call for
increased transparency at the world trade watchdog.
</P>
<P>
However, Ruggiero insisted that the WTO will continue to be run
by rules, not by powers.
</P>
<P>
He said that issues including opening Dispute Settlement
hearings and other WTO meetings to the public "can only be
approved by a consensus of member states."
</P>
<P>
"The same situation pertains to the issue of more rapid
derestriction of documents," Ruggiero told reporters at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
As part of the plan for cooperation with NGOs, Ruggiero said,
the External Relations Division of the WTO will begin a program of
regular briefings for NGOs on the work of WTO committees and
working groups.
</P>
<P>
The WTO secretariat will also extend each month to the 132 WTO
members a list of documents, position papers and newsletters
submitted by NGOs. These documents will be made available on
demand to WTO members.
</P>
<P>
The WTO will open a special section on its website to NGO
issues. The list of documents submitted to the secretariat by the
NGOs will appear on the site, as will all upcoming WTO symposia or
other events organized for the benefit of NGOs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
