<HEADLINE> Portuguese-Speaking Community to Send Contact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Community of
Portuguese-Speaking Countries meeting now in Praia, capital of
Cape Verde, has decided to dispatch a contact team to Guinea
Bissau to mediate for a peaceful solution to the armed conflicts
in the west African country.
</P>
<P>
They also resolved to send a delegation to East Timor to press
for self-determination in the country.
</P>
<P>
The two motions were initiated by Portugal and adopted by all
leaders attending the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The contact team, according to Portuguese Foreign Minister
Jaime Gama, will be made up of delegates from six
Portuguese-speaking countries namely Angola, Mozambique, Cape
Verde, Sao Tome &AMP; Principe, Portugal and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Cape Verde, which is the current executive chairman of the
Community, will lead the contact team and get in touch with the
Bissau government and the rebel militiamen as well as with the
United Nations, the Organization of African Unity and the
Economic Community of West African States.
</P>
<P>
Gama also revealed that the delegation to East Timor will be
headed by Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The Community of Portuguese-Speaking Countries was set up in
Lisbon, Portugal in July 1996. It is aimed at promoting
political and economic cooperation among the seven members.
</P>
</TEXT>
