<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Welcomes WTO Chief's Efforts for Better Cooperation With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States has praised the
World Trade Organization (WTO) Director-General Renato Ruggiero
for his efforts to improve the organization's cooperation with
non-governmental organizations (NGOs).
</P>
<P>
"Renato Riggiero has been the right man for the job in leading
members of this organization in the transition from the GATT into
the WTO," said Rita Hayes, U.S. permanent representative to the
WTO, in a statement issued here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The director-general has been providing the kind of pro-active
leadership the WTO needs at this point in opening up the system to
allow more interaction with 'stakeholders'," the U.S. trade envoy
said.
</P>
<P>
She expressed hope that the WTO chief's efforts in designing
and developing dialogue with the NGOs will be "very helpful to us
and all WTO members in building support for the initiatives likely
to be associated with the third ministerial conference" scheduled
to be held in the middle of November 1999 in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The success of that meeting and the launching of negotiations
will no doubt depend in part on the private sector believing that
it had a real input in developing the agenda," Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
In a proposal to the WTO General Council Wednesday, the United
States complained that the minutes of General Council meetings
generally come out only a month after the events, and even then
they are marked "restricted" and may remain unavailable to the
press and general public for as long as six months.
</P>
<P>
The same problem exists with panel reports, leading to
different interpretations by interested parties who would claim
victory by quoting parts of the reports, the Americans claimed.
</P>
<P>
In a speech on Wednesday responding to the United States'
proposal to increase the organization's transparency, Ruggiero
urged the General Council of the WTO to do more to promote
transparency and dispel the misleading impression of secrecy.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that no real progress will be made to improve the
exchange of information about the nature and goals of the WTO
unless there is a strong commitment from the governments of its
members.
</P>
<P>
As for the problems from the disclosure of panel findings of
the WTO dispute settlement body, Ruggiero put the blame on "the
fact that we are prevented from responding to, and correcting,
these inaccuracies by the rules of this organization." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
