<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workers at S. Korean Automaker Threaten Another Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The labor union at South Korea's
Hyuandai Motor Co. threatened Friday to stage a strike if the
management pushes ahead with its planned mass layoffs.
</P>
<P>
"We will go on strike indefinitely if the management lays off
workers," a union spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The threat came after the management, of the automaker with a
domestic work force of 45,000, said it will lay off 2,678 workers
under a corporate restructuring program.
</P>
<P>
The number of layoffs is down from the original 4,830. But it
still angered union workers who had returned to work Thursday
morning after a two-day strike to protest against the plan.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came hours after the labor union offered to
cut wages, benefits and other costs as an alternative to layoffs.
</P>
<P>
The union also urged the management to consider cutting work
hours, or allow job-sharing, but the management said such measures
were not enough to pull the company out of the business slump.
</P>
<P>
The company said 15,031 workers are either underemployed or
redundant. Of them, only 6,842 will be allowed to keep their
names on Hyundai's payroll through wage cuts.
</P>
<P>
The current financial crisis in South Korea has dented in the
nation's auto industry, causing Hyundai to operate only 50 percent
of its capacity.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai Motor is the first subsidiary of South Korea's large
conglomerates, or chaebol, to lay off workers. Other chaebol
subsidiaries suffering from sluggish business are closely watching
the Hyundai.
</P>
<P>
From Tuesday through Thursday, tens of thousands of workers
went on strike to protest against the government's forced economic
restructuring, which they claim will lead to mass layoffs.
</P>
<P>
Demanding an end to the program and the release of 83 arrested
union chiefs who led this week's strikes, the Korean Confederation
of Trade Unions (KCTU) and the Federation of Korean Trade Unions
(FKTU) have threatened to stage another general strike next week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government began Friday behind-the-scenes
negotiations with the labor community to defuse tensions.
</P>
<P>
An agreement signed last December with the International
Monetary Fund for a loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars to help the
economic recovery obligated South Korea to open its market, shut
down ailing financial institutions and restructure the economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
