<HEADLINE> S. Korean Banks' Bad Debts Could Hit 122 Billion US dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 17 (Xinhua) -- If the defaulted bill rate reaches
one percent this year, South Korea's domestic banks' bad debts are
expected to hit 157 trillion won (some 120.7 billion U.S.
dollars), Hyundai Economic Research Institute said Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a report, the institute said a yearly defaulted bill rate of
one percent is expected to increase commercial banks'
non-performing loans to 54.6 trillion won (about 42 billion
dollars) by the end of this year, up 40.4 percent from the 38.9
trillion won (about 30 billion dollars) as of March 31 this year.
</P>
<P>
If the debts at nonbanking institutions are included, the total
non-performing loans would swell to 79.5 trillion won (about 61
billion dollars) by the year-end, said the report.
</P>
<P>
These will push up total bad debts, including loans with
overdue interest payments for three to six months, to 157.2
trillion won (about 120.9 billion dollars) by the end of 1998,
compared with 112 trillion won (about 92.3 billion dollars) at the
end of March this year.
</P>
<P>
The institute, which said the defaulted bill rate in the
first-quarter period had already reached 0.72 percent even before
the government had conducted its financial and industrial
restructuring, predicted that the rate would easily top 1 percent
when the economic reforms get into full swing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
