<HEADLINE> 12 Countries Confirm Plans to Join NATO Albania Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Twelve countries have confirmed
their plans to participate in the planned NATO-led military
exercise scheduled for August 17-22 in Albania, a NATO official
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on condition of anonymity, the official said troops
from NATO and its Partnership for Peace member countries would
join in the peace support exercise code-named Cooperative Assembly.
</P>
<P>
It will involve paratroop drops, vehicle check-point controls,
close air support, forward air exercise and humanitarian aid in an
area some 100 kilometers away from Tirana, capital of Albania.
</P>
<P>
Initially planned for next year, the exercise was advanced by
the council meeting of NATO foreign ministers in May to reflect
its concern at the crisis in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The western military alliance carried out an air-borne exercise
with more than 80 airplanes last month in Albania and Macedonia to
demonstrate its ability to deploy troops rapidly in the region.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Britain, Germany, Greece, Spain, France and
Italy will join Albania in the exercise while Lithuania, the Czech
Republic, Austria, Denmark and Sweden will join rank as observers.
</P>
<P>
Russia has expressed interest in the NATO Albania exercise but
has not yet confirmed participation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
