<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Claim 1,000 Lives in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Floods have killed more than 1,000
people across China this year, according to the Ministry of Civil
Affairs today.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains which hit early March, and have been
especially heavy since June, have led to heavy flooding in a dozen
provinces and regions, mostly in areas south of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Regions seriously affected by flooding include Jiangxi, Fujian,
Hunan, Hubei, Guangdong, Sichuan, Anhui and Zhejiang provinces,
the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region and Chongqing Municipality.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu, Henan, Heilongjiang, Shaanxi and Shandong provinces,
as well as the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region also reported
problems related to minor flooding, according to the Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Statistics through July 15 show that floods have affected more
than 140 million people across the country. Floods have destroyed
some 2.9 million houses, decimated nine million hectares of crops
and caused direct economic losses estimated at over 84 billion
yuan (10 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
An official from the Ministry of Civil Affairs said that the
vast majority of deaths resulted from drownings, collapsing houses
and lightning.
</P>
<P>
"The efforts of health departments have prevented outbreaks of
epidemics in flood-stricken areas," according to the official.
</P>
<P>
He noted mud flows and landslides resulting from mountain
torrents have also caused many deaths.
</P>
<P>
"The results show the importance for protecting vegetation and
ecological environments in mountainous regions," said the
official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
