<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Claim 1,000 Lives in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Meteorologists say that many parts of China, especially areas
south of the Yangtze, have witnessed unusual extended periods of
heavy rainfall this year.
</P>
<P>
Various areas have reported rainfall accumulations expected
once every 100 years, while other areas have witnessed extended
periods of rain.
</P>
<P>
Local weather experts attribute the irregularities to "El Nino"
and point out that flooding occurred in China much more frequently
in the 1990s than in previous decades.
</P>
<P>
Flooding represented the major natural disaster China suffered
in 1991, 1994 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Sun Shaocheng, deputy director of the Disaster Relief
Department of the Ministry of Civil Affairs, said his ministry and
the Ministry of Finance have allocated 320 million yuan (40 million
US dollars) in relief funds to flood-stricken areas and
provided over 6,200 tents for homeless people.
</P>
<P>
He said governments at all levels in flood-stricken areas have
allocated over 300 million yuan to assist people in related areas.
</P>
<P>
"Flood waters have not as yet receded in certain areas in Hunan
and Jiangxi, with many people in said areas forced to live on
dikes and dams," according to Sun.
</P>
<P>
He predicted a decrease this year's summer grain harvest based
on the fact that flooding has seriously damaged early rice
cultivation in southern provinces.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists note the rain belt is moving northward, with
chances for major flooding diminishing.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, they warned of the continuing dangers of serious
flooding since China's rainy season usually ends in late August
and typhoons typically hit in the summer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Coral Reefs in Danger: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Human development is threatening
the future of nearly 60 percent of the world's coral reefs,
according to a recent study released here by the World Research
Institute (WRI).
</P>
<P>
Coastal development, overfishing and destructive fishing, and
pollution resulting from both land and marine based activities
are doing the most to destroy the reefs, the Kenya Times
newspaper Friday quoted the study as reporting.
</P>
<P>
The most threatened reefs are found in southeast Asia, where
an estimated 82 percent are considered to be at medium or high
risk, and more than half of the reefs in the Middle East, the
Caribbean and the Indian Ocean face similar degrees of threat.
</P>
<P>
"Like rain forests, reefs harbor much of the planet's wealth
of species and are being rapidly degraded by humans," said Dirk
Bryant, co-author of the report.
</P>
<P>
"Yet we know far less about the health of reefs than we do of
rain forests," he added.
</P>
<P>
The 56-page report, titled "Reefs at Risk", is co-financed by
WRI, the Nairobi-based U.N. Environment Program (UNEP), the
Britain-based World Conservation Monitoring Center (WCMC), and
the International Center for Living Aquatic Resources Management
in Manila.
</P>
<P>
Despite their long age -- some living coral reefs are 2.5
million years old -- very little was known about the extent and
condition of coral reefs until an initial survey of 108 countries
was completed by the WCMC in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The first global map depicting the location of shallow reefs
around the world was published by WCMC only in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Reefs occupy less than 0.25 percent of the earth's total
marine environment, yet they are home to more than a quarter of
all known marine fish species, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"Coral reefs are among the most valuable eco-systems on earth
because of their immense biological wealth and the economic and
environmental services they provide to millions of people," the
report said.
</P>
<P>
It's estimated that reef habitats provide human with living
resources, and services including tourism and protect inhabited
coasts from waves and storms, all of which worth almost 400
billion U.S. Dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Concern about these habitats has grown as more has become
known about them.
</P>
<P>
A widely-cited 1993 report asserted that ten percent of the
world's reefs were dead and another 30 percent were likely to die
within 20 years. However, the latest study said this was based
on anecdotal evidence and scientific "guesswork".
</P>
<P>
Even today, 90 percent of the world's reefs remain to be
comprehensively assessed for damage.
</P>
<P>
The report, dubbed by its authors as the "first systematic and
data-driven global assessment" of the reefs, is reportedly an
attempt to indicate the nature and extent of the major threats
the reefs face.
</P>
<P>
It was said that the report's conclusions "are a best
estimate, rather than a catalogue, of actual damage".
</P>
<P>
The report found that 58 percent of the world's reefs are
under high or medium threat from human activity.
Over-exploitation of fisheries and other reef resources as well
as coastal development represent about two-thirds of the threat.
</P>
<P>
The estimation probably is conservative because it does not
consider future threats such as population growth or global
warming caused by greenhouse gas emissions, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The study also found that the coral reefs in southeast Asia,
which are the most species-rich on earth, are also the most
threatened.
</P>
<P>
The study said the reefs of the southern Islands in Singapore,
the Bolinao Reef Complex in the Philippines, the Scarborough Reef
in the South China Sea and the Seribu Islands Reefs in the Java
Sea near Jakarta are among the 12 most threatened in the world.
</P>
<P>
Other danger spots include the Florida Keys Reefs in the
United States, the Bhia Las Minas Reefs near Panama, the Jamaica
reef off Jamaica, the Red Sea Riviera along the Gulf of the Aqaba
off Jordan, Israel and Egypt, and several reefs under U.S.
control in the central and western Pacific. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
