<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The Cypriot Government has decided to allow offshore
companies to invest in the Cyprus Stock Exchange in accordance
with a new amendment to the income tax law for offshore companies.
</P>
<P>
The amendment, which was passed by the House of
Representatives early this month, also provides for a five-year
tax break for newly-listed public companies, with 100,000 Cyprus
pounds (about 200,000 U.S. dollars) in profit as the maximum
allowance.
</P>
<P>
Investors are given tax breaks if they invest in newly-listed
local companies.
</P>
<P>
Previously, if an offshore company invested in businesses on
the island, it lost its beneficial income tax status.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus Airways Group registered losses in 1997 of
3.2 million Cyprus pounds (about 6.4 million U.S. dollars)
compared to 4.7 million pounds (9.4 million dollars) losses the
year before, Chairman of the Group, Takis Kyriakides, said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said the Group's total revenue reached 135.2 million pounds
(270.4 million dollars) in 1997 compared with 126.2 million pounds
(252.4 million dollars) the year before, registering a 7.1 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
Kyriakides explained that the Group's registered increase in
revenue was due to a 5.4 percent rise in the number of passengers
it carried, from 1,226,000 in 1996 to 1,292,000 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the Group's losses to the increasing labor
costs, which recorded a 5.3 percent increase compared with the
year before.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- Latest official statistics reveal that the volume of
Morocco's foreign debts have fallen for the first time below the
20 billion U.S. dollar level which has been kept for almost a
decade.
</P>
<P>
These figures indicate that Morocco's foreign debts amount to
19,096 million dollars, representing about 58 per cent of the
gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, these debts stood at 21.3 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
