<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Seeks to Improve Sea Ports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
committed to improving the overall condition of the country's two
sea ports to ensure the full use of trade opportunities in
external markets, an official handout said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Commerce and Industries Minister Tofael Ahmed made the remarks
while meeting a visiting mission of the Asian Development Bank
(ADB) here Thursday, the handout said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB mission is here to give a proper shape to a
167.5-million U.S.-dollar port efficiency and access improvement
project to be undertaken in the country.
</P>
<P>
The project includes the installation of modern quayside cargo
and container handling equipment in the country's two sea ports of
Chittagong and Mongla, the handout said.
</P>
<P>
With the implementation of the project, the private sector will
be a big beneficiary by being able to quickly dispatch their
imported and exported goods, thus making a good impact on the
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has been maintaining an export growth rate of over
17 percent, the minister said, adding that the country plans to
expand the annual export from the present 5.2 billion dollars to
8-10 billion dollars by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
The government is trying to improve the infrastructure
facilities like setting up of a deep-sea port at Patenga Point
southeast of here to cope with the country's fast-growing trade,
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"Port operation should be efficient and competitive, and we are
trying to ensure it for the exporters and importers." 
</P>
</TEXT>
