<HEADLINE> Buddhist Theological Institute to Increase Enrollment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Buddhist Theological Institute
of China plans to double its enrollment following completion of a
new teaching building.
</P>
<P>
Monk Sheng Hui, vice-president of the institute, said today
that the institute will enroll over 200 students every two years,
or twice the former enrollment of 90 students.
</P>
<P>
The new building will be completed at a cost of 11 million yuan
raised by Buddhist monks and followers from both at home and
abroad.
</P>
<P>
The two-story building, which will have a total floor space of
2,348 square meters. will feature classrooms, offices and storage
rooms for Buddhist classics.
</P>
<P>
Venerable Zhao Puchu, president of the institute and the
Buddhist Association of China, said the Buddhist institute was the
first of its kind funded by the central government.
</P>
<P>
The institute, which was established in 1956, was closed during
the "Cultural Revolution" (1966-1976) and reopened in 1980. The
300-odd monks trained at the institute have grown into the pillar
of Chinese Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
China currently has 24 Buddhist theological institutes offering
instruction in Chinese.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
