<HEADLINE> Swaziland May Curb S. African Cheap Food Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Swaziland's agricultural
industry, reeling from the effects of cheaper food products
flooding in from South Africa, plans to respond with increased
levies and border inspection, Business Day newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland's National Agricultural Marketing Board (Namboard),
alleged that South African goods, ranging from fresh produce to
dairy products, were dumped in Swaziland and said that the matter
was being taken up with the Southern African Customs Union which
both South Africa and Swaziland belong to.
</P>
<P>
The paper Friday quoted Namboard leader, Magalela Ngwenya,
as saying that his organization was likely to ask the Swazi
Agriculture Ministry to set levies on the offending food imports.
</P>
<P>
He said the dumping was attributable to different factors,
chief among them the South African government's move last year to
shut down control boards.
</P>
<P>
This resulted in cheap produce flooding South Africa from
overseas, to the ultimate detriment of Swaziland, said Ngwenya.
</P>
<P>
When wheat flour from South Africa flooded the Swazi market
late last year, local industries lost 1.5 million Rand (about
300,000 U.S. dollars valued at that time) every month in the last
quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
Namboard estimates that the "dumping" of South African produce
onto the Swazi market incurred losses of 3.5 million Rand
(700,000 dollars) last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
