<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Reviving Up Operations in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping
force, ECOMOG, has moved 94 percent of its troops from Liberia to
Sierra Leone in a bid to enhance the mopping up of remnants of
the junta forces and allied rebels in that country.
</P>
<P>
Progress has been made despite some logistic problems, said
ECOMOG Force Commander Timothy Shelpidi, quoted by This Day
newspaper Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian general claimed that his troops, in their mopping
up exercise, have gone round the Kono district which is very
mountainous.
</P>
<P>
But things are now not easy for ECOMOG because the rebel
juntas know very well the environment of the areas where have
been their base and hideouts, particularly with the coming of the
raining season, he noted.
</P>
<P>
A lot of bridges have been destroyed by junta men, thus
delaying ECOMOG's operations as the areas are not easily
accessible, he added.
</P>
<P>
Despite the difficulties, ECOMOG has captured many rebels who
afterwards surrendered their weapons, while others are willing to
surrender.
</P>
<P>
The general said he had been expecting the support from the
United Nations which recently decided to send an observers
mission to the tiny west African country. 
</P>
