<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: HK's Information Policy Remains Unchanged: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's policy on press
freedom remains unchanged after its return to China last July,
said Thomas Chan, director of the Information Services Department
(ISD) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua at his office, Chan said: "our
information policy is very simple. We respect freedom of the press
without any regulations to control news reporting. The media are
expected to play a part in supervising the government and can
report freely without restriction except in the areas of
pornography, defamation or court proceeding as specified under the
law."
</P>
<P>
He said that the secretary for home affairs has overall
responsibility for policy formulation on information and related
matters, while the director of the ISD advises the government on
the presentation of its policies and on public relations matters
generally, both within Hong Kong and overseas.
</P>
<P>
"The main aims are to ensure an open exchange of information in
the community and to keep the media fully informed of the
government's plans and policies, so that members of the public are
kept aware of government activities which affect their lives, and
to promote Hong Kong's image overseas," he added.
</P>
<P>
There are now about 50 daily newspapers, more than 600
periodicals, 3 television stations and 3 radio stations as well as
about 150 foreign media organizations in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
During the hour-long interview, Chan said that the Central
Government has never tried to change Hong Kong's present
information policy since the SAR was established one year ago.
</P>
<P>
He said local residents enjoy the same freedom of speech and
publication after Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
The ISD serves as the government's public relations consultant,
publisher, advertising agent and news agency. It provides the link
between the administration and the media and, through the latter,
enhances public understanding of government policies, decisions
and activities.
</P>
<P>
With a staff of more than 500, the ISD is operating as usual
after the handover, he said. It publishes on the Internet a daily
information bulletin in English and Chinese which contains all
government press releases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: HK's Information Policy Remains Unchanged: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISD staff worked long hours as so many important events, such
as the handover ceremony, the Annual Meetings of the World Bank
and the International Monetary Fund as well as the Legislative
Council election, took place one after another in Hong Kong over
the past year.
</P>
<P>
"In order to increase transparency and openness of the
government, we try to arrange more direct dialogues between
government officials and local residents over the past year, thus
making them know more of each other's views," he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the ISD maintains direct contact with the media on a
24-hour basis and answers media's inquiries round the clock.
</P>
<P>
Chan said that a key objective of the government's information
policy is to project an accurate image of Hong Kong overseas.
</P>
<P>
To maintain the international community's interest in Hong Kong
after the handover, the government has stepped up promotional
activities overseas.
</P>
<P>
Both Administrative Secretary Anson Chan and Financial
Secretary Donald Tsang went abroad to tell foreign business people
 how well Hong Kong has managed the transition and that Hong Kong
is still an ideal place not only for investment but also for
tourism, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, to enable local people to know what happens in
Hong Kong in the shortest possible time, the ISD has made great
efforts to realize the computerization of its work ranging from
news compilation to news release and publicity design.
</P>
<P>
Chan, who is well versed in computer knowledge, launched the
first government home page in San Francisco introducing Hong Kong
to the world before he came to the ISD.
</P>
<P>
The ISD established an Internet Resource Center last year to
help bureaus and departments set up home pages and to consider how
the government could improve the dissemination of information
through better use of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
It also introduced a new digital photo system last July,
through which photos can be sent to media organizations and news
agencies via a computer network.
</P>
<P>
"We are concentrating our efforts on improving our work by
developing more advanced computerized system to meet the needs of
customers and continuously maintain Hong Kong as an international
information center," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
