<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judicial Independence Fully Maintained in Hong Kong: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The top law official of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of the People's Republic
of China said that Hong Kong's judicial independence has been
fully maintained and protected after its reunification with China.
</P>
<P>
Elsie Leung, Secretary for Justice of the Hong Kong SAR who is
in Singapore on a visit, made the remarks at a luncheon Friday
jointly organized by the Hong Kong Economic and Trade Office in
Singapore and the Singapore Academy of Law.
</P>
<P>
Leung told about 1,000 law officials and experts from Singapore
that the "history will record that Hong Kong's reunification with
China was achieved smoothly and that the legal system, the rule of
law, human rights, and the independence of the judiciary have been
fully maintained and protected."
</P>
<P>
In a post-luncheon interview with local and foreign reporters,
she also said that nothing that falls within the power of the SAR
under the Basic Law has been interfered and the central government
has been very supportive of the SAR in exercising its power.
</P>
<P>
Continuity of Hong Kong's own laws has been upheld and the SAR
enjoyed the full support from the central government, she added.
</P>
<P>
Leung briefed the participants on the key events that have made
judicial independence possible.
</P>
<P>
Leung said Hong Kong is proud to have been reunified with China
and Hong Kong will develop a body of jurisprudence in respect of
the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Leung arrived in Singapore Wednesday for a three-day visit at
the invitation of Singapore's Attorney General Chan Sek Keong
under the Singapore-Hong Kong Civil Service Exchange Program.
</P>
</TEXT>
