<HEADLINE> NZ Government to Put 5.2 Million US Dollars Into </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government
announced here on Friday that it was putting 10 million NZ dollars
(5.2 million U.S. dollars) into the year 2000 millennium
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Internal Affairs Minister Jack Elder said that the money was
separate from the Lottery Grants Board funding. The board is
expected to contribute 10 million NZ dollars as well.
</P>
<P>
Elder said that the "national vision" for the celebrations
would be "that New Zealand will lead the world into the third
millennium by celebrating and exploring our nationhood in ways
which excite the imagination of people everywhere". The main theme
would be "First to the Future", he added.
</P>
<P>
"New Zealanders have said they want the celebrations to
communicate pride in being a New Zealander and in New Zealand's
achievements, while at the same time having fun and enjoying
themselves," Elder said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
