<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Troops' Return Is Routine Exercise : Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The return of some 3,000 Nigerian
soldiers from Liberia has nothing to do with Nigeria's security
situation, the Defense Headquarters said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Defense spokesman Godwin Ugbo denied speculations that
the Nigerian soldiers are pulled back from the west African
peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) to beef up security in the country at
the critical time of the military government's transition to
civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
"It's a rumor because the rotation of soldiers to serve ECOMOG
is a routine exercise," said Ugbo.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman told Xinhua that the redeployed
soldiers who have served in the Nigerian contingent of ECOMOG for
three years would be replaced by another set of 3,000 fresh
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Arrangements have been concluded by the military authorities
to move another three battalions of troops to ECOMOG in a
replacement for the three battalions that are expected to arrive
from Saturday in four batches.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian-led ECOMOG has succeeded in ending the nine-year
civil war in Liberia and restoring the elected government of
Sierra Leone which was ousted in a coup in May last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
