<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SKorean Foreign Currency Reserve Rises to $41.88 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 17 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's foreign currency
reserve jumped to 41.88 billion U.S. dollars as of July 15, an
increase of 980 million dollars from the end of last month, the
central Bank of Korea said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The usable foreign reserve, which excludes domestic banks'
deposits at overseas branches, also grew 1.05 billion dollars to
38.09 billion dollars in the period.
</P>
<P>
The bank attributed the rise of the usable foreign reserve to
the domestic commercial banks' repayment of an additional 640
million dollars to the central bank, which extended emergency fund
to the commercial banks after the financial crisis took place late
last year due to corporate failures and bad loans of financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Domestic banks have returned 12.2 billion dollars of the
emergency fund they borrowed from the central bank. In the future,
they have to pay back 11.09 billion dollars to the bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
