<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan MPs Want Speaker Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
They voiced the outcry Thursday during a discussion at the

NRM's first national congress being held here, the New Vision paper

reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Holding both public offices concurrently is unconstitutional,

they said, because it causes inefficiency, duplicate work and

compromises the legislature.
</P>
<P>
Aggrey Awori, a MP from Samia Bugwe North, was quoted

as saying that those who have accepted new appointments

should vacate their seats in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Wapakhabulo and several other MPs appointed

directors to the NRM secretariat, a senior Movement leader said on

condition of anonymity: "These people must go otherwise we shall be

seen to be greedy and bending the law to suit our needs."
</P>
<P>
In Uganda, the constitution bars MPs from holding two public

offices at the same time while the Movement National Executive

Committee has allowed the MPs to hold both offices.
</P>
<P>
All ministers in Uganda are MPs and they are supposed to

support the bills presented to the floor by the government.
</P>
<P>
At present, the name of First Deputy Prime Minister and Minister

of Foreign Affairs Eriya Kategaya has been floated for the post of

Speaker.
</P>
<P>
Under the constitution and rules of procedure of Parliament, once

the office of Speaker falls vacant, the office must be filled before

any business can be conducted by Parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
