<HEADLINE> Saddam Says Sanctions on Iraq Crumbling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
said on Friday that U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq are crumbling
and would end soon with Iraqis' steadfastness, unwavering position
in demand of lifing the blockade.
</P>
<P>
In a nationally broadcast speech on the 30th anniversary of
1968 revolution, that brought his Baath party to power, the Iraqi
president expressed the hope that "this year, and the time that
follows will be the year and time of virtual erosion of the
blockade off Iraq."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed the sanctions on Iraq in 1990 after its
invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president tried to play down the expectations
of the people by saying that "the blockade will not be lifted by a
unanimous U.N. Security Council resolution."
</P>
<P>
"Rather," he added, "it will erode -- the more Iraqis remain
firm in their position, the more the implications of this
position" will attract the attention of the Arabs and the rest of
the world.
</P>
<P>
The president mentioned the open letter addressed to the
U.N. Security Council and secretary-general on May 1 this year,
which demanded immediate lifting of trade embargo off Iraq as a
prelude to lift the overall U.N. sanctions off Iraq, and warned of
severe consequences if the Council failed to respond to the letter
positively.
</P>
<P>
"It (the letter) was not a mere outcry of protest, but an
expression of determination and an alternative strategy," should
other means fail, the president cautioned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
