<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Minority Pupils Village For Frontier Education (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- In an outlying mountainous part of
southwest China's Yunnan Province, the flag is raised every Monday
morning in a unique "village" composed of more than 280 pupils and
12 teachers.
</P>
<P>
The village is actually a primary school of Yunlong County,
with a two-story building, a rough playground in front, and a
number of log cabins scattered here and there.
</P>
<P>
The cabins were designed and built by the pupils and serve as
private dormitories, because, unlike the more prosperous boarding
schools in urban areas, the pupils of this school come from poor
families and have to look after themselves.
</P>
<P>
The first cabin was put up by Zhang Yiqing who studies and
lives in the 10-square-meter room he built with timber and pieces
of wood.
</P>
<P>
His classmates come from the village of Tiandeng, where 560
households are scattered across a 168-sq km area, quite a
distance from the primary school, so they followed Zhang's lead
and gradually turned the small campus into a village.
</P>
<P>
When the school lets out at four o'clock in the afternoon, the
pupils return to their cabins to prepare supper. Li Jinyan, a
first-year pupil, is standing over a pot of corn gruel on the
stove. And a cupboard holds buckwheat flour and dried vegetables,
and nearby is a little bed with a worn cotton-padded quilt.
</P>
<P>
The girl said that her parents used to come all the way here to
cook for her, but as she gradually got used to looking herself,
they came less and less, with the exception of weekends, when they
would take her home or bring her food, vegetables and firewood,
and other supplies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Minority Pupils Village for Frontier Education (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhang Wendi, the headmaster of Lisu ethnic group, said that Li
Jinyan's story is a fairly typical one for the 281 pupils who, in
spite of all their difficulties and hardships, have done the best
they could, listening attentively in class, and then continuing to
study by candlelight beside their beds at night.
</P>
<P>
Tiandeng has approximately 2,700 people, the majority of whom
belong to the Lisu ethnic group. Half of them have to work very
hard just to feed themselves, and are certainly not able to save
anything. But, no matter how destitute they may be, they never
keep their children at home and away from school.
</P>
<P>
Yang Maochun, a 76-year-old villager, for example, has been
helping his daughter-in-law keep her two children at school ever
since their father died last year.
</P>
<P>
Yang Yuemei, another villager, manages to keep both her own
children and her younger sister at school. Her parents have been
dead for a long time.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, 33 of the pupils at the village are
orphans. The village committee managed to allocate 440,000 yuan
(53,000 US dollars) from its 600,000-yuan (72,300 US dollars) in
funds to build a small hydro-electric power station for the
school. On June 1 of this year, International Children's Day, the
county education bureau sent the pupils sport uniforms, so, for
the first time they had uniforms.
</P>
<P>
And, the local government provides every pupil with a small
monthly stipend to help get over some difficulties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0145 </DOCNO>
