<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall in Tokyo After 4 Days of Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices fell in Tokyo Friday
following a previous four straight day increase due to a lack of
fresh buying incentives.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange dropped 161.14 points, or 0.96
percent, from Thursday's close to end at at 16,570.78.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 2.78 points or 0.22 percent to 1,277.95.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section came to an estimated 400 million
shares, down from Thursday's 446.76 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan (LTCB) was the day's most
heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Friday's drop was widely expected, considering that the Nikkei
had climbed 640 points, or almost four percent, over the four
previous days of trading.
</P>
<P>
Traders have repeatedly said that for the Nikkei to keep its
upward momentum, the market would need a truly significant boost,
such as the announcement of a major permanent cut in income taxes
as a means to revive consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
But many analysts predict such bold measures will not take
place until after the July 24 Liberal Democratic Party
presidential election, at which outgoing Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto's successor is expected to be elected.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,332 issues listed on the First Section, losers
exceeded gainers 612 to 496, with 161 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
