<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania"s Trade With Central Europe Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Romania's trade with Central
European countries grew rapidly after it joined the Central Europe
Free Trade Agreement (CEFTA) a year ago, the ministry of industry
and trade said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Figures issued by the ministry show that in 1997, Romania's
total volume of trade with these countries exceeded one billion
U.S. dollars, a nearly 20 percent increase over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Despite its trade deficit with other CEFTA members, with
imports almost double exports, Romania's exports in the second
half of 1997 increased 70 percent over the same period of 1996.
And in the first quarter of 1998, Romania saw exports 19.3 percent
higher than the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Hungary and Poland are Romania's main trade partners in CEFTA.
Trade with these two countries last year reached 529 million
dollars and 191 million dollars respectively. Romania's trade is
also growing with Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
Romania signed the CEFTA on April 12, 1997, and became an
official member on July 1 the same year. The CEFTA, which was
launched on December 21, 1992 by Poland, Hungary and former
Czechoslovakia, now has six members, Poland, Hungary, the Czech
Republic, the Slovak Republic, Slovenia and Romania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
