<HEADLINE> Obuchi, Kajiyama to Run For LDP Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo
Obuchi and former Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama
expressed their intentions Friday to run in the Liberal Democratic
Party's presidential race to succeed Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, 61, told a news conference that if elected "I will try
to resolve the difficulties at any cost."
</P>
<P>
"As a politician it is my mission to revive the Japanese and
Asian economies with all possible means and to tide over the
biggest difficulties since the end of World War II," Obuchi said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi said he would also adopt a style of politics independent
of bureaucrats and promote negotiations with Russia to conclude a
peace treaty by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Kajiyama, 72, also said at a meeting of veteran and other LDP
lawmakers that he will run for the LDP presidency, Kyodo News said.
</P>
<P>
"I am determined to do my best by entrusting my body and spirit to
all of you," Kajiyama was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The new LDP president is sure to become prime minister because
the LDP holds a majority in the House of Representatives (lower
house), which will elect a new prime minister on July 30.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto submitted his resignation as LDP president Monday to
take responsibility for the LDP's major setback in last Sunday's
House of Councillors (upper house) election.
</P>
<P>
Besides Obuchi and Kajiyama, another influential LDP faction
led by former Finance Minister Hiroshi Mitsuzuka, is also prepared
to field either Health and Welfare Minister Junichiro Koizumi or
LDP General Council Chairman Yoshiro Mori for the election,
according to Mitsuzuka faction sources.
</P>
<P>
A total of 413 LDP members are eligible to vote in the race,
which is expected to be held on July 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
