<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading British Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading British newspapers Friday:
</P>
<P>
The Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Ministers are considering banning blood transfusions from
British donors because of the remote risk that they might spread
Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, the human form of "mad cow" disease.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Telegraph:
</P>
<P>
-- Shoppers face higher prices for "designer" items, including
Calvin Klein clothes and Levis, perfume, sportswear and champagne,
after a thriving trade in cut-price goods was outlawed by the
Eueopean Court of Justice yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The Independent:
</P>
<P>
-- A combination of Tory backwoods peers, bishops, and Labor
rebels was last night preparing to overturn the massive Commons
vote to lower the age of consent for gays to 16.
</P>
<P>
Financial Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Lockheed Martin and Northrop Grumman, the US defence
companies, yesterday called off their planned 11 billion dollar
merger after negotiations aimed at finding a formula that would
satisfy US government concerns collapsed.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian:
</P>
<P>
-- Private security guards patrolling Britain's streets will
soon be a common sight, under plans being drawn up by chief
constables. 
</P>
