<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stable Nigeria Best for Africa: Says OAU Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The successful democratization of
Nigeria will be in the interest of the entire African continent,
said Salim Ahmed Salim, the Secretary-General of the Organization
of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
Salim arrived here Thursday for a meeting with Nigeria's Head
of State General Abdulsalam Abubakar scheduled for Friday in the
capital Abuja, the official New Nigeria newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief, who came to Nigeria at the invitation of
Abubakar, said that the meeting would go a long way to help in
resolving series of problems facing the most populous African
country.
</P>
<P>
Salim said that OAU's interest in the country's affairs did
not narrow down to business alone but anything that would promote
peaceful co-existence in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever happens here concerns all the people of Africa. We
have stake in the future of this country. A stake that will
promote stability," Salim said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that given the sad moments the country had gone
through, it would be ideal for every Nigerian to see the present
political situation as an opportunity to advance a virile
governance.
</P>
<P>
"The transition program is essential in Nigeria, we will do
what is required of us, not only on Nigeria's problems but also
in African affairs," Salim added.
</P>
<P>
Salim's visit followed those by his counterparts in the United
Nations, Kofi Annan, and the Commonwealth, Emeka Anyaoku, who
ended their visits to the country earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
According to Salim, the pan-African body is very happy with
the developments in Nigeria, especially at this difficult
and challenging time.
</P>
<P>
"We are very much encouraged with the steps taken by the head
of state so far. We wish Nigeria to pursue the path we have
always advocated, the path to democratic dispensation," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers on Friday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The diplomatic offensive by Syrian President Hafez al-Assad in
France coincided with a series of actions at home in preparation for
his succession. Assad recently made a number of purges in the
military institutions and replaced the mayors of several majors
cities of his country, in an initiative to reform the country which
for a long time has neither political life, nor economic initiative,
nor transparency.
</P>
<P>
-- The Spanish judicial authorities has closed a newspaper which
is close to the armed wing of the Basque separatist group ETA. The
closing of the daily ``Egin'' has caused strong backwash in Spain,
because it was the first of its kind since the end of the
dictatorship of General Franco.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The head of the finance commission of the National Assembly
Didier Migaud Thursday presented concrete proposals on the reform of
France's private fortune tax, the ISF, which is expected to raise
the income from the tax by 2 billion francs (333 million U.S.
dollars) each year. The Communist proposal to include professional
properties, or working tools, into the ISF has been abandoned.
</P>
<P>
-- The threat by the government to impose tax on ownership of
objects of arts is handicaping the French arts market which is
seeing an exodus toward New York and London. However, the first half
of 1998 has been encouraging with a 10 percent rise of transactions
in Paris arts market, mainly because of a 51.5 billion francs (8.6
billion U.S. dollars) transactions of the works of Eugene Delacroix
at the Drouot, Paris's biggest arts marketplace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
