<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Sugar Firms in Crisis Over Cheap Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Leading Kenyan sugar companies
are facing a marketing crisis following dumping of cheap imports,
officials from sugar industry and the Federation of Kenya
Employers (FKE) have complained.
</P>
<P>
The companies are holding large stocks of sugar which they
cannot sell due to saturation of the market with cheap imports.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is pretty bad," Western Kenya FKE Chairman
Absolom Moseti said Thursday. "The companies, which are our
members, are again facing a marketing crisis and this is causing
them serious cash flow problems."
</P>
<P>
According to Moseti, sales of most companies have dropped by
over 50 percent in the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
A Mumias Sugar Company official said that they have over
20,000 tons of sugar in their stores, saying the company is
unable to get market for the commodity.
</P>
<P>
"The stocks are simply not moving... this is causing the
company cash flow problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We recently reduced our sugar prices to see whether we could
compete in the market," said the company official.
</P>
<P>
Chemelil Sugar Company said it has stocks worth over 178
million Shillings (some 2.97 million U.S. Dollars), while Sony is
stuck with stocks worth 200 million Shillings (about 3.33 million
U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
"If the problem persists, the company might just be forced to
close down," said an official with the Chemelil company.
</P>
<P>
Mumias usually crashes 8,000 tons of sugar a day with Sony and
Chemelil each 3,000 tons. The three are among the largest sugar
companies in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's annual consumption of sugar stands at 560,000 tons
while its total production is about 400,000 tons, the East
African Standard newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, after the market liberalization at the end of 1980s,
Kenya's sugar industry bore the brunt in the so-called transit sugar
dumping in the local market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
