<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, July 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Bosnian Serb Republic President Biljan Plavsic has
threatened to cut contact with a senior international
representative in Bosnia who said that the necks of many Bosnian
Serbs should be "twisted."
</P>
<P>
In a Sarajevo-based newspaper, Hanns Schumacher, Deputy High
Representative of the Peace Implementation Council, criticized the
Republic Srpska for failing to carry out the repatriation of
refugees and threatened to impose sanctions against the republic.
(Bosnia-Srpska-Schumacher)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The hostilities in Kosovo ought to be stopped
immediately and the process of negotiation be restarted, the
Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhamin said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Kosovo has a tendency for aggravation, said
Rakhamin while commenting on the on-going visit by a delegation of
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe. He condemned
terrorism and splittism and appealed to Kosovo ethnic Albanians to
stop their armed actions and enter into negotiations without
preconditions. (Russia-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- President Bill Clinton on Thursday signed papers
authorizing a renewal, for another six months, of the waiver of
the Helms-Burton law that requires the United States to penalize
foreign firms investing in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he signed the papers because the United States and
its allies in Europe and Latin America had been increasing
cooperation to promote changes in Cuba. (US-Cuba-Sanctions Waiver)
</P>
</TEXT>
