<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key Eastern Chinese Bridge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Workers started stringing two
principal cables on a bridge across the Yangtze River at the city
of Jiangyin in east China's Jiangsu Province on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bridge is a key infrastructure project of China's Ninth
Five-Year-Plan and an important part of the Tongjiang
(Heilongjiang Province)-Sanya and Beijing-Shanghai national
highways that are expected to be finished before the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The steel-cable suspension bridge will have a main span of
1,385 m. long, the longest in China and fourth in the world.
</P>
<P>
The two 866-mm cables have a combined weight of 17,000 tons and
will take 100 days to be installed.
</P>
<P>
Work on the bridge started in November of 1994 and is scheduled
to be completed on October 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this June, 2.2 billion yuan had been spent on it,
260 million yuan of that from overseas investors, accounting for
66.1 percent of total expenditures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
