<HEADLINE> Kenya, Malaysia Urged to Cooperate in Vegetable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan and Malaysian companies
have been urged to start joint venture companies to develop the
vegetable oil industry in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Kassim Owango, Chairman of the Kenya National Chamber of
Commerce and Industry, was quoted by Friday's Daily Nation
newspaper as saying that such a firm could also import vegetable
oils for re-export to neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Enhancing processing food oil industry can both create job
opportunities for Kenyans and reduce the dependence on imported
vegetable oils and fats, he said at a seminar organized by the
Malaysia Palm Oil Promotion Council ending Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kenya, where only 4,000 tons of oils are produced locally,
spends nine billion Shillings on the importation of 400,000 tons
of the oils per year, said Owango.
</P>
<P>
The eastern African country further spends 500 million
Shillings of oil seed cake and animal feeds, he said.
</P>
<P>
Raj Kumar Shah, the deputy managing director of Josovina, one
of the leading suppliers of palm oil to east Africa, said the
high tariffs on crude oil products discouraged trade between
Malaysia and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Kenyan government to lower the charges, calling
for the establishment of palm oil plantations in Kenya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
