<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector Growing In Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The private sector in China's
Qinghai Province, a sparely populated and underdeveloped area on
the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, has become a major source of local
employment and revenues.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts attribute the growth in the private economy to
government support in recent years.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the private sector was employing more
than 300,000 people, accounting for a third of the total in urban
areas. Nearly 20,000 people who had been laid off at state-owned
companies have found new employment with private enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, private businesses here paid 94 million yuan in taxes,
an increase of 33.9 percent from the previous year, and by the end
of 1997, there were 70,000 private or household businesses in
Qinghai, compared with 46,350 five years before.
</P>
<P>
Annual industrial output of the private sector increased by 35
percent to about 700 million yuan last year, and sales went up to
3.2 billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
