<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Railway Traffic Increases in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Trains in China carried a total of
2.28 million passengers last month, an increase of 2.7 percent
over the same month last year, according to latest statistics from
the Ministry of Railways.
</P>
<P>
Within this figure, the number of long-distance travelers,
those going more than 500 kilometers in one journey, reached
557,000, up 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ministry officials attribute the increase to faster trains, a
greater number of rail lines and improved train services.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that trains carried 69,800 carloads of
goods on a daily average, including 26,860 cars of coal, nearly
the same level as last year. The number of train-delivered
containers in June was 260,000 TEUs (twenty-foot equivalent units)
or 2.23 million tons, up 4.2 and 8.6 percent, respectively, from
the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The transport of other key materials such as oil, minerals,
and fertilizer also met their monthly targets.
</P>
<P>
No serious train accidents occurred last month, although floods
hit a number of railway lines, officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
