<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Trade Deficit Continues to Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The balance of trade in goods from
January to May 1998 continued to decline in the Philippines,
dropping by 66.1 percent to 1.603 billion U.S. dollars from 4.725
billion dollars a year ago, the National Statistics Office said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Revenue from exports increased by 20.3 percent to 11.515
billion dollars from 9.571 billion dollars a year ago while
payments for imports dropped by 8.2 percent to 13.118 billion
dollars from 14.296 billion dollars, a report from the office
showed.
</P>
<P>
Merchandise trade for the first five months in 1998 grew by 3.2
percent to 24.633 billion dollars from 23.867 billion dollars last
year.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of electronics and components, still the top import
item with a 28.9 percent share, grew by 46.9 percent to 757.58
million dollars from 515.83 million dollars last year, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
It also showed that trade deficit in May alone dropped by 78.5
percent to 209 million dollars from 971 million dollars over the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The United States, which accounted for 25.4 percent share of
the total imports, was the biggest source of imported goods for
the month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
