<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese People Are Best Friends of Zimbabwean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
said the Chinese people are the best, the closest and most
reliable friends of the Zimbabwean people.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks Thursday when he met in Harare the
delegation of the Communist Party of China (CPC) headed by Huang
Ju, member of the CPC Political Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said that during the most difficult years of the Zimbabwean
people's struggle for national independence, the Chinese people
went through thick and thin together with Zimbabweans.
</P>
<P>
After independence in 1980, Zimbabwe got a lot of valuable
assistance from China in defending national independence and
reconstruction, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean president said that tremendous changes have
been taken place in China in the past few years. There is much
successful experience China has made that Zimbabwe can make use
of, he added.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who is also president and first secretary of the
ruling Zimbabwe African National Union-Patrotic Front (ZANU-PF),
expressed the hope that the existing friendship between the CPC
and the ZANU-PF will be further developed and cooperation areas
be continuously expanded.
</P>
<P>
Huang Ju, who is also Secretary of the CPC Shanghai Municipal
Committee, conveyed the best regards from Chinese President Jiang
Zemin and Premier Zhu Rongji to President Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Huang said China and Zimbabwe have traditionary friendly
relations. The two countries always support each other, having
forged a profound friendship between the two countries and
parties.
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of the important contributions the Zimbabwean
president has made in developing bilateral ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the CPC and the Chinese government attach
great importance to promoting friendship and cooperation in the
political, economic and cultural areas with Zimababwe.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation arrived here Wednesday for a four-day
visit to Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
