<HEADLINE> Tibet Gets Endemic Disease Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA July 17 (Xinhua) -- Lhasa, the capital of China's Tibet
Autonomous Region, now has an endemic disease hospital thanks to
generous Hong Kong citizens.
</P>
<P>
The hospital, which bears the name of China's famous
philosopher Confucius, was built with 800,000 Hong Kong dollars
(about 90,000 U.S. dollars) in donations by Hong Kong citizens to
a fund headed by Dr. Tang Enjia, head of the Hong Kong Institute of
Confucianism, and 400,000 yuan from the local government.
</P>
<P>
The 400-sq.m. hospital will focus on research and treatment of
such endemic diseases in the region as iodine deficiency, the plague,
and fluorine poisoning. 
</P>
