<HEADLINE> Old Chinese Industrial Center Reports Moderate Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Economic development in Liaoning
Province, a leading heavy industrial center in northeast China,
maintained moderate growth in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The GDP was estimated at 142.7 billion yuan by the end of June,
up 6.5 percent from the same period of last year, the director of
the Provincial Statistics Bureau, Pei Zhiyuan, told a press
conference on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The retail price index had negative growth for the first time
in the past 20 years and the consumer price index was down 0.7
percentage points, compared with the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The new characteristics of economic growth, Pei says, are
steady local industrial development, with a 9.1-percent rise in
the first half. Fixed asset investment was also up 8.3 percent to
reach 23.56 billion yuan in the first six months.
</P>
<P>
Consumer goods sales amounted to 71.5 billion yuan and revenues
were 10.49 billion yuan, a 13.7 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
However, because of the Southeast Asian financial crisis, the
growth rate of exports of this coastal province dropped 4.9
percentage points and that of imports was down 24.7 percentage
points. Foreign investment took a nose dive of 8.9 percent
to 1.2 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
