<HEADLINE> Private Businesses Boom In Northeast China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Harbin, capital of northeast
China's Heilongjiang Province, has had 195,000 private businesses
by the end of June, a 15 percent increase from the same 1997
period.
</P>
<P>
These businesses employed 384,000 people, also a 15 percent
rise. They have generated 1.35 billion yuan in output value this
year, up 28 percent from that in the same 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
The rapid growth in private business in Harbin, one of the
country's traditional industrial bases, is attributed to the local
preferential credit, tax, and business policies.
</P>
<P>
The city now has 27 private enterprise groups and more than
5,000 private corporations.
</P>
<P>
Local private undertakings have expanded from the service
sector to agriculture, education, infrastructure, real estate, and
intermediate service.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of this year, 100 state and collective
enterprises were even purchased by big private enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
