<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gansu-Xinjiang Railway in Northwest China Restores Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The only railway from
Gansu Province to the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region in
northwest China returned to normal operation early morning today
after having been out of commission for 85 hours because of heavy
rainfall.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains hit the area on July 14 and rain continued
over the past several days, causing flooding that destroyed 25
sections of railway in a 43-kilometer stretch from Shisanjianfang
station to Liaodun station, local railway administration officials
said.
</P>
<P>
The damage stranded 63 trains carrying 14,000 passengers, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
At least 1,000 workers from the Urumqi Railway Administration
in the region's capital, along with 160 pieces of heavy equipment
were rushed to the site to repair roadbeds and help move the
stranded passengers to safety.
</P>
<P>
The workers have repaired all damaged roadbeds and restored
transportation to normal on the 1,892-kilometer railway line,
which is an important link between Lanzhou, the capital of Gansu
and Urumqi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
