<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Taxi Fare Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Beijing residents may be paying
less for taxis in the coming months, municipal taxi administration
officials suggested here today.
</P>
<P>
A price adjustment is expected to cover all taxis, from the
most luxurious to the cheapest, a senior official has said, but
did not provide a specific timetable or plan for the proposed
cut. Administration officials are talking with taxi drivers and
soliciting opinions.
</P>
<P>
Fares for Beijing's 67,000 taxis range from 1 yuan (0.12 U.S
dollar) to 2 yuan per kilometer. the 31,000 taxis that charge 1.6
yuan per km, may cut their fare by 13 to 25 percent, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
Fewer tourists, more concentrated bus routes, and the
increasing number of private cars have meant a sluggish year for
the taxi business and authorities have been thinking about a price
cut for a long time.
</P>
<P>
Taxi drivers are reported to be earning much less because of
the decrease in the number of riders. In addition, "black" or
gypsy taxis, which have no permit, are eating into the shrinking
market. Some departments estimate that the city has more than
20,000 of these taxis operating throughout the city, and a fare
cut might help drive these illegal taxis out of the market.
</P>
<P>
Each taxi driver with a permit has to pay several thousand yuan
in taxes and other expenses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
