<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colleges Aim at New Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- A course in management will be
part of the curriculum of China's colleges and universities next
year in a move aimed at furthering the country's economic and
social development in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
It is being added to the 10 major subjects already
studied: philosophy, economics, law, education, literature,
history, science, engineering, agronomy and medicine, the Ministry
of Education announced at a press conference here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to today's China Daily, some specialities have also
been merged and condensed, which is part of the country's higher
education reform program for the next few years.
</P>
<P>
The curriculum adjustment is intended to widen the students'
knowledge and improve their ability to cope in the competitive job
market today, said Zhong Binglin, director of the ministry's
Higher Education Department.
</P>
<P>
The ministry readjusted the specialities in 1989 to cater to
China's rapid economic and social growth under reform policies,
introducing 504 specialities.
</P>
<P>
But with the transition from the previous planned economy to
today's socialist market economy they fail to fully meet economic
needs, said Zhong.
</P>
<P>
Starting in 1994, the Ministry of Education invited 10,000
university professors to readjust the 504 specialities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
