<HEADLINE> Polish Government to Raise Grain Purchasing Amount </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Polish government Thursday
agreed to the demands of resentful farmers to increase grain
purchases and limit grain imports.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Council of Ministers Jerzy Buzek told
agriculture organizations representatives that the government
would double the planned grain purchase to 15 million tons this
year.
</P>
<P>
The lowest purchase price for wheat and rye will be 510 zlotys
(147.8 U.S. dollars) per ton and 360 zlotys (104.3 dollars) per
ton respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to the Polish Press Agency, Buzek also said that the
government has taken measures to stop importing grain and to
increase import tariffs
</P>
<P>
But the new tariff policy would come into force after August 6,
under international and domestic laws, he added.
</P>
<P>
Last week, thousands of dissatisfied farmers and agriculture
organization activists demonstrated before government and National
Assembly buildings in the center of Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
The farmers, opposing the present agriculture policy of the
government, demanded an end to grain importing and an increase in
finance for agriculture.
</P>
<P>
They also asked Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Finance
Leszek Balcerowicz to resign.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration, the largest since 1992, was broken up by
police and 15 farmers were wounded in clashes with police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
