<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Plays Down Confrontation with Nicaragua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican Public Security
Minister Juan Rafael Lizano maintained today that armed police
must be able to navigate the border River San Juan, despite a ban
on their movement by the Nicaraguan army.
</P>
<P>
Lizano said today that President Miguel Angel Rodriguez would
discuss the issue with his Nicaraguan counterpart Arnoldo Aleman
in San Salvador during the meeting of Central American Presidents.
</P>
<P>
Under the Treaty of Limits between the two countries, the river
is under Nicaraguan sovereignty, but Costa Rica insists that it
has the right to navigate freely where the river forms a common
border for almost 200 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The Nicaraguan Army forbade the movement of armed police boats
to their border posts this week is what is believed to be
retaliation for Costa Rica's increased deportations of illegal
Nicaraguan immigrants.
</P>
<P>
According to the Costa Rican Foreign Affairs Ministry, the
number of Nicaraguans illegally entering Costa Rica has reached
600,000 accounting for almost 20 percent of the total population.
</P>
<P>
The cheap Nicaraguan labor has caused disorder in labor market
and the social services in Costa Rica, according to the Costa
Rican government.
</P>
<P>
Police deployments have been intensified along the frontier to
prevent Nicaraguans from entering Costa Rica. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
