<HEADLINE> Illegally-Seized Money Returned to Real Owner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- In the interest of justice, the
Luanxian People's Court recently returned 520,000 yuan (62,650
U.S. dollars) of illegally confiscated money and money orders to
their owner, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The return of the money corrects a case involving eight judges
who allegedly abused their power.
</P>
<P>
The judges will receive due punishment soon, according to
officials at the court and the Communist Party committee at
Luanxian County in north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
In November 1997, the court in Hebei settled a contract dispute
involving a 550,000 yuan (66,265 U.S. dollars) no-interest loan.
</P>
<P>
In March this year, the court sent special representatives to
Guangdong to force compliance at the request of plaintiff,
Tangshan Industry and Commerce Corp, when the defendant, Guangdong
Meixian Taorao Cement Factory failed to comply with the court
order. The effort was fruitless.
</P>
<P>
In April, the case took a twist when a note provided by the
defendant claimed he had brought the money to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Eight judges from the court ransacked a place where two people
from Guangdong Angel Advertising Co., who had no connection to the
court case, were staying and seized 520,000 yuan (62,650 US
dollars) in money and money orders from the advertising company
representatives.
</P>
<P>
Luo Xingsheng, the advertising company representative, said
that he and his company's general manager Liu Yue'e came to
Beijing planning to use the money to buy a batch of special
out-of-use stamps for serviceman.
</P>
<P>
They were to buy them from Chen Hualin, a legal representative
of Tangshan Industry and Finance Corp.
</P>
<P>
Luo had been told by Liu Mu, a sponsor of the cement company,
that the stamps were in large demand in the market.
</P>
<P>
After seizing the money and money orders, the court incorrectly
deposited the money under Li's name the same night, and gave
480,000 yuan to Chen five days later, ignoring the money owner's
legitimate protests.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Guangdong Angel Advertising Co. has not appealled
to the court for compensation, according to the Luanxian People's
Court.
</P>
<P>
No others have been charged in the case, but the investigation
has not ended. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
