<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Offshore Oil Corporation Striving to Be More Profitable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) --China Offshore Oil Corporation will
strive for greater profits on the basis of maintaining last year's
crude oil output of 16.28 million tons, according to today's
"Economic Daily."
</P>
<P>
The company will also use all possible means to reduce
production costs and ensure a profit of 700 million yuan this year.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, oil prices on the
international market have been plunging, with the drop-off as much
an estimated 40 percent compared to last year's levels.
</P>
<P>
Under the prerequisite of maintaining the same oil and gas
output this year as last, the company is likely to suffer a loss
of 30 million yuan by the end of the year based on estimates of
current oil prices and production costs.
</P>
<P>
The corporation will also take steps to lower salaries and
make its employees aware of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
They will also make efforts to advance reform and tighten
management, treating the reduction of production cost as a
long-term task to bring down the cost of producing one barrel of
oil from 13.26 U.S. dollars to ten U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
China began to peg crude oil prices to the international market
on June 1 this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
