<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Urges EU to Restore Preferential Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Thailand, citing its economic
crisis, has urged the European Union (EU) to restore preferential
tariffs on several categories of Thai goods, a government official
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Thai officials made the request at a recent meeting with EU
officials in Bangkok, according to Apinan Pavanarit,
director-general of the European Affairs Department of the Thai
Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
EU officials are expected to make a decision in September on
Thailand's eligibility for the Generalized System of Preferences
(GSP), which allows developing countries to export to the EU
countries at reduced tariff rates.
</P>
<P>
Brussels should use Thai economic figures for 1997 as the basis
for their decision, said Apinan.
</P>
<P>
The restoration of the GSP would affect tariff rates on nine
key Thai exports -- fishery products, vegetables and fresh fruit,
processed food, plastic products, hides and furs, precious metals,
rubber products, clothing and shoes.
</P>
<P>
GSP privileges for six categories of industrial goods were
removed last January. They have been cut back by 50 percent on
three categories of agricultural goods and are scheduled to be
removed completely next January 1.
</P>
<P>
Thailand wants to export 6,300 tons of shrimps to Europe under
a special, non-GSP quota at a six percent tariff rate, but the
request faces opposition from France.
</P>
<P>
France is said to be interested in protecting shrimp exports
from its overseas territories, including the Indian Ocean island
of Reunion.
</P>
<P>
Brussels recently proposed a draft law allowing a special quota
for imports of 6,300 tons of tropical shrimps from all over the
world at the six percent tariff rate.
</P>
<P>
Thailand hopes to secure the quota because it is the only
country whose GSP for fishery products has been cut. As a result,
exporters are paying 18 percent tariffs to enter EU markets,
Apinan said.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the EU has proposed a social support
program for Thailand worth 675 million baht (16.8 million U.S.
dollars) to create jobs and improve liquidity in the agricultural
and non-agricultural sectors. The program would include technical
assistance, loans and soft loans.
</P>
<P>
The program will be considered in October and could begin early
next year after the signing of a financial agreement, Apinan said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
