<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- The Lima Stock Exchange rose 6.2 percent during the
first half of this month, a significant recovery from June, when
the stock index dropped more than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
This rise was attributed to the relative stability of the Asian
economies, the agreement of economic assistance to Russia from the
International Monetary Fund, and the resignation of Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Some 26 foreign consortiums will take part in
the auctioning of the stock of four state firms that generate
electricity in Panama.
</P>
<P>
The consortiums interested in the bidding are 15 from the
United States, two each from Switzerland, Spain and England, and
one each from Colombia, Chile, Belgium, Canada and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said the auction will be held on September 10.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian soluble coffee exports amounted to 18,700
tons (813,000 bags) during the first six months of this year, a 19
percent reduction against the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian Association of the Soluble Coffee Industry
reported that the political and economic problems faced by African
countries and Russia were the main factors for the drop of the
Brazilian soluble coffee exports.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The World Bank will grant a loan of one billion
U.S. dollars over five years to finance "a market agrarian reform"
in Brazil, according to the World Bank Department for Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
The program is being carried out in five Brazilian states with
150 million dollars provided by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguayan Central Bank international reserves
increased 197 million U.S. dollars in the first six months of this
year to a total of 2.263 billion dollars, or 11.3 percent of the
gross domestic product, at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
Three years ago, the international reserves of this country
were 1.43 billion dollars, eight percent of the gross domestic
product.
</P>
</TEXT>
