<HEADLINE> Beijing Protecting Old Trees in Temple </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 100 ancient trees at the
Jietai Temple in the western suburbs of Beijing have been getting
better protection in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Gardeners in the temple have spent a million yuan on protecting
a number of pines that are more than 1,000 years old, by applying
fertilizer and special nutritional elements.
</P>
<P>
The trees are threatened by decay that is caused by their
inability to absorb nutritional elements. To prevent rainwater
from seeping inside the tree trunk, the gardeners cleaned out the
dead wood and stuffed the tree trunks with a preparation of
anti-rot material and insecticides.
</P>
<P>
The Jietai Temple was built in 622 and is one of Beijing's
better known tourist attractions because of its ancient pine
trees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
