<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rican central government finances showed a
149 million U.S. dollar deficit in the first half of this year, 15
percent less than the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the Finance Ministry showed that, during the first
half of this year, central government total income reached 831.8
million dollars, and total spending was 981.2 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Direct foreign investment (DFI) in Venezuela in the
first half of this year amounted to 1.33 billion U.S. dollars,
according to the Industry and Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
New DFI amounted last June to 13.54 million dollars, which was
distributed among the manufacturing, commerce, real estate, and
other financial services, as well as in cultural services and
entertainment, transportation, warehousing, and communications.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Petroleos Mexicanos (Pemex), a state-owned oil
company, has confirmed the reduction of 200,000 barrels of crude a
day in its exports to fulfill the commitment to stabilizing the
international oil market.
</P>
<P>
Pemex said that at the close of August, average exports for the
month would be 1.64 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The Chilean foreign debt amounts to 28 billion
U.S. dollars, according to preliminary figures for last May 31, as
reported by the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Of that total, 27 billion dollars correspond to medium and long
term and only one billion dollars to short term debt.
</P>
<P>
Public sector debt amounted to 5.4 billion dollars, while that
of the private sector was 22.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- The price of Colombian coffee for export
closed Wednesday at 1.22 dollars a pound as against the 1.83
dollars registered last February.
</P>
<P>
Colombian Coffee National Exporters Association president
Gabriel Rosas Vega said that the big processing firms have ordered
no more coffee until the quotation drops below one dollar per
pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
