<HEADLINE> China's Economy Expected to Pick up in Second Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- China's economic growth is
expected to rebound in the second half of 1998 after a slow slide
during the first six months, "Shanghai Securities News" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
This conclusion is based on a report by the economic research
institute under the State Development Planning Commission. The
institute gives four reasons:
</P>
<P>
-- China's reform of its reserve fund, the most effective in
the financial reforms, is expected to yield better results in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
-- The volume of investment is on steady rise and construction
of additional new projects has commenced, and the property market
is now healthier.
</P>
<P>
-- Bank loans have increased noticeably.
</P>
<P>
-- Local governments have all set their own minimum economic
growth rates and are taking measures to ensure the fulfilment of
their economic targets.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the price of production has been slightly reduced.
</P>
<P>
All these indicators point to an economy that is recovering,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
China's economic growth rate was registered seven percent for
the first six months, one percentage point lower than the
projected eight percent for the annual target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
