<HEADLINE> China Dredging Its Second Largest Fresh Water Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Eight Dredgers have been moved to
China's Dongting Lake in the middle Yangtze River valleys to
improve its ability to withstand natural disasters like flooding.
</P>
<P>
The lake was once the largest in China, and has shrunk to second
position because of the large amount of sand, that has flowed into
it and which is increasing at a rate of nearly 100 million cubic
meters each year.
</P>
<P>
The sand deposits have also lessened the lake's use in
controlling flood because it can no longer serve as a natural
catch basin as it did in the past, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The dredgers can move more than 50,000 cubic meters of earth
each day, and the southern part of the lake will be connected to
its eastern part when the dredging project is finished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
