<HEADLINE> Successful Operation Separates Siamese Twins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Siamese twins born 13
days ago in Argentine's Mendoza province were separated
successfully in a surgical operation Wednesday, in a hospital in
the province.
</P>
<P>
Ana Belen and Laura Noelia, who were born united by the
buttocks in the sacrum region on July 3, and weighing 2.7 and 2.6
kilograms respectively, now sleep for the first time in separate
incubators and in perfect health.
</P>
<P>
The separation operation lasted five hours with the
participation of 32 doctors and nurses in cutting the meningeous
sacrum, which the two babies shared, and sectioning it by the
sacrum region.
</P>
<P>
To guarantee the success of the operation, the surgeons made a
colotomy 10 days ago to evacuate the big intestine for the
prevention of infection.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that one more simple operation will be performed
three months later to close their annuses and open their anal
conduits, and if necessary, more surgery would be done on the
lower sides of their backs.
</P>
<P>
The medical doctors said the twins shared no vital organs, or
bone structures, but only a union of soft tissues extending 10
centimeters.
</P>
<P>
The little sisters will have a normal life after the
operations, said the doctors.
</P>
<P>
This was the first such operation in Mendoza province, in the
west of Argentina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
