<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Condemns West on Drozdy Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Russia's State Duma (lower house of
parliament) on Thursday condemned the United States and West
European countries over the Drozdy embassy compound dispute with
Belarus.
</P>
<P>
The Duma said the Western countries had no reason to take
extreme action and isolate Belarus for the expulsion of diplomatic
staff from homes in Drozdy, in the capital city of Minsk.
</P>
<P>
The Duma issued an appeal to parliaments of the member
countries of Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe,
the ITAR-TASS news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Duma said in the appeal that the Drozdy compound was where
the Belarus presidential residency was located and that Belarus
had good reason to ask foreign embassies to move out of the
compound.
</P>
<P>
According to the Vienna Convention on Diplomatic Relations
signed in 1961, the decision of a sovereign state should be
respected, the appeal noted.
</P>
<P>
The United States and West European countries should not have
denied visas to senior Belarus officials, or threaten to break off
diplomatic relations, which were obviously politically-motivated
moves and intended to magnify the event.
</P>
<P>
The dispute over the Drozdy compound started two months ago
when the Belarus government ordered diplomats to quit the
compound, saying that extensive maintenance was required on the
buildings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
