<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Renews Helms-Burton Waiver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Thursday signed papers authorizing a renewal, for another six
months, of the waiver of the Helms-Burton law that requires the
United States to penalize foreign firms investing in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he signed the papers because the United States and
its allies in Europe and Latin America had been increasing
cooperation to promote changes in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
"Events in the past six months reaffirm that international
cooperation for Cuban democracy is increasing," Clinton said in a
statement notifying Congress of his decision.
</P>
<P>
"I made this decision to take advantage of the growing
realization throughout the world, in Europe and Latin America
especially, that Cuba must change. We see progress on many
fronts," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was the fifth time Clinton has waived the provision since
the law went into effect in March 1996. Each waiver has a
six-months life span, after which it expires unless it is renewed.
</P>
<P>
The Helms-Burton law has enraged U.S. allies in Europe and
Canada. They accused Washington of pursuing extra-territoriality
by penalizing foreign companies that invest in Cuban property
seized after the 1959 Cuban revolution. They vowed to retaliate if
the United States enforced the law against their companies
investing in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Even Clinton has complained about the rigid law despite the
fact that he signed it. He said it constrained his ability to
conduct foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
The ground work for the latest waiver came in an agreement
reached in May between U.S. and European negotiators. The European
Union agreed to adopt certain "disciplines" to inhibit and deter
investments by its businessmen in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Clinton himself has worked to improve some contacts with Cuba,
allowing Cuban families in America to send more money back home to
relatives and easing restrictions on charter flights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
