<HEADLINE> Cuba, Jamaica Tighten Ties with New Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Cuba and Jamaica signed here a
letter of understanding on Thursday which aims to forge closer
ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the foreign affairs ministries of the two
countries will exchange information and consult each other on
topics of common interest as well as regional and international
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Upon the signing of the agreement, Roberto Rabaina, foreign
minister of Cuba praised the Caribbean states, and especially
Jamaica, for their support in the struggle against the United
States' economic embargo.
</P>
<P>
Seymour Mullings, the Jamaican foreign minister said the
agreement will strengthen ties between the two countries, and his
government was pleased to see Havana granted the status of
observer in the Asia-Caribbean-Pacific Group.
</P>
<P>
Mullings, who was also the vice prime minister and foreign
trade minister of Jamaica, ended his four-day official visit to
Cuba Thursday afternoon. During his stay he talked with President
Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
In May 1997 Jamaican Prime Minister James Patterson visited
Cuba, thus beginning a warmer relationship between Kingston and
Havana.
</P>
<P>
On that occasion the two countries signed three bilateral
agreements about the promotion and reciprocal protection of
investments, sports cooperation, and exemption of visas for
diplomatic, official and service passports.
</P>
<P>
With their government's urging for a total integration of Cuba
to the Caribbean Community of Nations, Jamaican investors are
taking an active part in the development of the Cuban tourism
industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
