<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Carbon Tax Expected in 1999 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 16 (Xinhua) -- A tax on carbon dioxide emissions,
which are responsible for the "greenhouse effect", was promised
Thursday for the 1999 Italian budget, an environmental expert said.
</P>
<P>
Gianni Silvestrini, senior expert with Italy's Environment
Ministry, said the measure was one of Italy's moves to cut its
emissions of greenhouse effect gases by 6.5 percent of 1990 levels
before the end of 2010.
</P>
<P>
The cut is part of the package agreed at the Kyoto environment
summit in December last year. The Italian figure is part of an
overall pledge from the European Union to cut the emissions by
eight percent by the same deadline.
</P>
<P>
Silvestrini said the carbon dioxide tax would be used to
encourage the use of less polluting energy sources and coordinate
moves to cut Italy's 100,000 tons of carbon dioxide emissions each
year.
</P>
<P>
Italy was the only nation to take a national climate plan at
the Kyoto summit. The plan contains concrete measures to cut
emissions in transportation, energy, industry and waste management.
</P>
<P>
In its last version, the plan proposed investments of around 91
trillion lire (around 50 billion U.S. dollars) for emission
reduction over the next 12 years.
</P>
<P>
The main targets are the cars and trucks clogging Italian
roads. Many of them are old and big pollution generators, although
the government's soon-to-expire incentive scheme for the
demolition of older cars has reportedly ensured some gains in
terms of lower pollution.
</P>
<P>
Energy producers are expected to cut the gases by four percent
by the deadline as renewable energy sources develop.
</P>
<P>
Household appliances, of which Italy is Europe's leading
producer, are also a major source of greenhouse gases, and they
will be singled out for an incentive scheme to replace with the
new generation of appliances generating less pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhaoqing Bridge Getting Bank Loans for Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Zhaoqing Bridge Co. Ltd. of south
China's Guangdong Province will borrow 250 million yuan in bank
loans to finance construction of Zhaoqing bridge, "China Daily"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The 7.8-km-long bridge is one of Guangdong Province's key
projects planned for the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
The company signed a contract on borrowing the loans with
Guangdong Development Bank yesterday.
</P>
<P>
"The credit is one example of the bank's commitment to
assisting construction of infrastructure projects in the province
and to aiding the province to achieve a 10 percent economic
growth," said Li Rouhong, President of Guangdong Development Bank,
at a contract-signing ceremony held in Guangzhou, the provincial
capital.
</P>
<P>
According to Li, his bank has granted the city six billion yuan
in credit loans, mostly for energy and transportation projects.
The bank has also reached a preliminary agreement with China
Infrastructure Construction Investment (Zhaoqing) Co. Ltd. to
raise 1.8 billion yuan for the Guangzhou-Zhaoqing highway project.
</P>
<P>
Besides the loans to Zhaoqing, the development bank has lent
money elsewhere in the province. It has granted 150 billion yuan
in loans for provincial economic development since it was founded
a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
Energy, transport, communications and trade top the list of
bank-funded projects such as the Guangzhou-Meizhou-Shantou
Railway, Dongguan highway, Shunde Desheng Power Plant and Huizhou
Dongjiang Power Plant.
</P>
<P>
The bank, which is a commercial bank with a total assets
exceeding 90 billion yuan, has also helped develop private
enterprises, lending money to Shenzhen Huaqiang Group, Shenzhen
Gas Group and Shenzhen Sega-Hitachi Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Total deposits at the bank are valued at 55 billion yuan.
Loans are valued at more than 40 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Entrusted by the People's Bank of China, the development bank
last year merged with China Finance Trust and Investment Corp., a
non-banking financial institution on the verge of bankruptcy, at
the cost of five billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
