<HEADLINE> Greater Economic Growth For South China Port City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIHAI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The GDP in Beihai, a port city in
south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, was up 14.5 percent in
the first half of the year, compared with the 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
The city's exports and foreign investment were up 49.8 percent
and 62 percent respectively, a city government official said.
</P>
<P>
The growth is attributed to a diversified economy, with various
types of ownership having been tried in the city, he said.
</P>
<P>
Profits from tourism increased 7.1 percent from the same period
of 1997. The property market had a resurgence and did 389 million
yuan worth of business in the first six months, 58 percent more
than the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Beihai had 15 foreign-funded enterprises in the first half of
this year, with contracts worth 53.9 million U.S. dollars, up 62
percent over the same period last year. 
</P>
