<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Child Sex Abuse Happens at Home in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Ninety percent of sex abuse of
children in Italy takes place at home within the family and is
usually perpetrated by a father or by a step-father, says a study
released by the Center for Social Investment Studies (Censis)
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The study shows only eight percent of such abuse occurs outside
homes and by persons known to the child, such as teachers, school
personnel or other professionals dealing with minors.
</P>
<P>
In barely two percent of the cases, the child is the victim of
a perfect stranger, the study shows.
</P>
<P>
Every year in Italy 10,500 to 21,000 children, or two out of
every 1000 children, fall victim to rape or sexual assault, it
says.
</P>
<P>
Censis said it was able to put together this report on the
sexual exploitation of minors with the help of justice and
interior ministries.
</P>
<P>
It was found that the number of complaints lodged against
strangers was 64 in 1997, compared with 30 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, police reports were up sharply with regard to charges
of child rape by individuals known to the victims: 406 in 1997,
compared to 275 in 1996, 172 in 1995, 135 in 1994 and 167 in
1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moroccan El Guerrouj Runs Second-fastest Mile Ever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Moroccan Hicham El Guerrouj ran the
second-fastest mile in history at an international athletics
meeting in Nice on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
El Guerrouj, who improved Noureddine Morceli's 1,500-meter
record in Rome on Tuesday, just missed taking the Algerian's mile
record of three minutes, 44.39 seconds as he was timed 3:44.60 in
the Nice meeting.
</P>
<P>
The race was expected to be a showdown between Guerrouj and
Morceli but the Algerian withdrew just six hours before the start
of the meeting with a pulled muscle in his right thigh.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday El Guerrouj clipped 1.37 seconds from the listed
1,500m world record set by Morceli on the Nice meeting last year.
</P>
<P>
The Nice meeting also produced four other season best marks.
</P>
<P>
World record holder Javier Sotomayor of Cuba cleared a season
best height of 2.34 meters to win the men's high jump from
American Olympic champion Charles Austin, who finished second with
2.30m.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Bernard Barmassai, the 3,000m steeplechase world record
holder, won the event with the season's best performance of
8:01.53.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 3,000m, Morocco's Zahar Ouaziz took the title
with a season best time of 8:28.66 followed by Ireland's Sonia
O'Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
The women's 400m hurdles champion went to world record holder
American Kim Batten who clocked a season best time of 53.17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economy Grows Seven Percent in First Six Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese economy grew seven
percent year-on-year in the first half of this year, the State
Statistics Bureau announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The Gross Domestic Product totaled 3.4731 trillion yuan during
the January-June period, up seven percent, Ye Zhen, the bureau's
spokesman, told a press conference this morning.
</P>
<P>
The half-year industrial incremental value, meanwhile, grew 7.9
percent to 920.9 billion yuan, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that China's investment in fixed assets totaled
582.8 billion yuan in the first six months, up 13.8 percent from
the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The price level remained low in the first half of this year,
with the retail price index falling 2.1 percent and the consumer
price index, which also cover the cost of services, inching down
0.3 percent, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Between January and June, China's contractual overseas direct
investment totaled 24.2 billion US dollars, up 5.5 percent on a
yearly basis, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, paid-in direct overseas investment edged down 1.3
percent to 20.5 billion US dollars for the six-month period, Ye
said.
</P>
<P>
Overall, it's not easy for China to maintain stable economic
growth under the situation of accelerating pressure of the Asian
financial crisis, insufficient domestic demand and serious natural
disasters, Ye told the press conference.
</P>
<P>
"And this indicates that the policies and measures taken by the
Chinese government are utterly correct and effective," he said.
</P>
<P>
So long as the polices to boost domestic demand are earnestly
followed in the second half of this year, China's economic growth
will pick up and the eight percent growth target for this year's
national economy can be realized, Ye Zhen affirmed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Urged to Curb Dumping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine business community
has raised an alarm over the rising incidence of dumping and urged
the government to curb the practice by putting in place tougher
measures and sanctions to violators.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Star Friday quoted President of the Federation
of Philippine Industries Antonio Garcia as saying that unless
dumping, smuggling and undervaluation problems were addressed by
the government, "there would be no more domestic industries to
speak of."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference held here Thursday, Garcia said
that aside from revenue losses to the government, dumping, where
imported products are being sold at cheaper prices than in their
source countries, is hurting local industries.
</P>
<P>
"Industries are losing market share and people are losing their
jobs," Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 400,000 workers were laid off between July 1997
and May 1998 in manufacturing, service and construction sectors as
a result of the crippling financial crisis, exacerbated by dumping
practices, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said countries like South Korea and Thailand have resorted
to dumping goods in the country in an attempt to sell their
products and compensate for weak demand in their beleaguered
economies.
</P>
<P>
"We must devise a procedure where this problem can be addressed
expeditiously," Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
Since there are market disruptions in other countries, he said,
the Philippines must protect its own turf by putting restrictions
on imports, such as fixing a growth ceiling which was an earlier
proposal endorsed by the trade department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0265 </DOCNO>
