<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Cuts Export Target for 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
lowered its export target this year to 29.7 billion U.S. dollars
from the original 30 billion dollars due to the slowdown in
electronics shipments, a newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sergio Ortiz-Luis, president of the Philippine Exporters
Confederation, was quoted by the Philippine Star as saying the
revised export target can be met if the present currency exchange
stabilizes and global demand-supply situation holds up.
</P>
<P>
The government, which had expected the country's exports to
boom due to the peso devaluation, revised downward the export
target because of the slowdown in electronics exports, the
country's top dollar earner, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This (downscaling) was in reaction to small product sectors
that we felt will not make any headway in exports this year,"
Ortiz-Luis said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said the electronics sector, which accounts for a
commanding 58 percent of aggregate exports, is reeling from weak
global demand and is thus expected to post a 25-percent growth
this year.
</P>
<P>
"It would not be difficult for electronics to hit a 30 percent
growth but it would be reasonable to peg its growth at 25 percent,
from a 32-percent expansion last years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, the government set the export target at 30
billion dollars, a slower 20-percent growth from last year but
still better off than the rest of the region, notably former
export pace-setter Thailand and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
In the first five months of 1998, earnings from merchandise
exports went up by a strong 20.3 percent to 11.5 billion dollars
from 9.6 billion dollars a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, export receipts reached a record 25 billion dollars, a
substantial 22 percent increase from the previous year even as the
currency turmoil hit the Asian region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Sticks to ASEAN's Non-intervention Principle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam sticks to the principle of
non-intervention" in dealing with ASEAN member countries, a
Foreign Ministry spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman, Phan Thuy Thanh, made the remarks Thursday at
press conference when asked to comment on Thailand's proposal for
ASEAN to adopt a policy of "flexible engagement."
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal, ASEAN members can comment on their
partner's domestic matters when they have regional implications.
</P>
<P>
"The basic principles guiding the activities of ASEAN are
consensus, consultation and non-intervention," said the
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
She said these principles, which are written in the Treaty on
Amity and Cooperation (TAC), have guided ASEAN to strengthen
solidarity and development over the past years and will continue
to do so in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
When joining ASEAN, Vietnam declared that it will respect TAC
and the country has always honored these principles, she said.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN (the Association of Southeast Asian Nations) groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, the Philippines, Malaysia, Myanmar,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
