<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Villagers Suffer From Respiratory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Some 1,800 villagers living west
of Mt. Merapi in Central Java, Indonesia, are suffering from
respiratory ailments by inhaling volcanic ash, Antara News Agency
Friday quoted a local doctor as saying.
</P>
<P>
The villagers could have avoided inhaling the ash if they had
worn protective masks but the local health office did not have
enough supply, Dr. Edy Suharso, who is based in Krinjing village,
Dukun sub-district in Central Java, said.
</P>
<P>
The Merapi, one of the most active volcanoes in Indonesia,
erupted last Saturday (July 11), raining volcanic ash on Dukun and
its outlying areas. But no casualty has been reported.
</P>
<P>
The volcano's activity has subsided since then but it continues
to release clouds of hot gas, although they are smaller.
</P>
<P>
Every time Mt. Merapi spews out thick clouds of dust, villagers
living around experience eye, throat and skin irritations, the
report quoted local villagers as saying.
</P>
<P>
Officials have recently lowered the warning level from "danger'
to "alert", but they advised those living near the volcano to
prepare for evacuation although an imminent eruption is not
expected.
</P>
<P>
Merapi last erupted in November 1994, killing at least 60
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
