<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Trade Unions to Be Set Up in Foreign-Funded Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- China's top labor organization
wants trade unions in at least 80 percent of all foreign-funded
ventures in China and collective bargaining in at least 40 percent
of such firms, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Tian Yukun, an official with the
All-China Federation of Trade Unions, as saying that these goals
will be reached with help from local governments and increasing
acceptance of unions among foreign-funded ventures.
</P>
<P>
The union claims that 54,000 foreign-funded enterprises, or
three quarters of the eligible ventures, were unionized in
accordance with China's labor law and collective bargaining, by
the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 percent of the employees have joined the
newly-organized unions, said Tian, who oversees trade unions in
foreign-funded firms.
</P>
<P>
"Since 1994, we have made it a must that before foreign-funded
companies start, they have to think about forming trade unions,"
Tian said. "And when the venture is opened, the union should begin
to work at the same time," he added.
</P>
<P>
By the end of March, 1998, 23,297 foreign-funded firms had
signed collective contracts, accounting for 43 percent of the
unionized firms.
</P>
<P>
About 5,000 foreign-funded firms are expected to ink collective
labor contracts, Tian said.
</P>
<P>
The collective contracts cover salary, working hours, working
conditions, insurance, welfare benefits, labor disputes and job
descriptions.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese official also noted that the legitimate rights of
trade unions and union officials carrying out their duties are
protect by law.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
