<HEADLINE> All Doping Tests Negative in Soccer World Cup Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 16 (Xinhua) - All doping tests carried out at the
1998 soccer World Cup finals were negative, the sport's world
governing body FIFA said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
About 35 per cent of the 704 players in the 32 competing teams
underwent random urine tests after their matches, FIFA said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"Taking only the semifinalists into account, 64 percent of the
players from these four teams had undergone tests for prohibited
substances at least once," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"All the doping tests carried out at the 1998 World Cup proved
to be negative."
</P>
<P>
Under FIFA rules two players from each team are tested after
every match following a random draw made at halftime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
