<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Scoops Gymnastics Medals in World Youth Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Gymnastics powerhouse Russia won
four golds in artistic and rhythmic gymnastic competitions in the
World Youth Games Thursday as more countries and regions elbowed
their way into the rank of medal winners.
</P>
<P>
Besides the four gymnastic golds, Russia also captured five
titles in athletics and swimming, bringing its total of golds to
30. China came second, with golds totaling nine, in addition to
three silvers and two bronzes.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-one countries and regions are now on the list of medal
winners, up from 43 Wednesday, with medals distributing in all
continents except Oceania.
</P>
<P>
Russia beat Ukraine in both junior men and girls artistic
gymnastic team contests. The third place went to Belarus for
junior men and Spain for girls.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's rhythmic gymnastics events were also dominated by
Russia, which won two golds, two silvers and one bronze. Ukraine
snatched the only remaining medal of the day, a bronze.
</P>
<P>
One of the focuses of attention on Thursday was a press
conference with Juan Antonio Samaranch, president of the
International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
The fate of any future World Youth Games was as uncertain as
ever. Samaranch told reporters that international Olympic
officials would review a report on the first World Youth Games in
Russia in Lausanne, Switzerland, next September and then decide
the "continuation or non-continuation" of the games.
</P>
<P>
As to Moscow's ambition to hold the 2012 summer Olympics,
Samaranch refrained from express endorsement, saying only that the
Russian capital is a strong candidate.
</P>
<P>
In junior men's volleyball quarter-finals Thursday, Russia beat
Belarus 3-0; Czech Republic defeated Chinese Taipei 3-2; Brazil
trounced Poland 3-0; and Ukraine eliminated France 3-1.
</P>
<P>
For girls' quarter-finals, Russia beat Ukraine 3-1; China beat
Germany 3-0; Italy beat Brazil 3-0; and Poland beat Croatia 3-1.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, junior women's handball semi-finals will be fought
between Russia-Poland and Ukraine-Lithuania. There will also be
junior men's semi-finals between France-United States and Czech
Republic-Egypt.
</P>
<P>
More medals are expected to come out on Friday in freestyle
wrestling, artistic and rhythmic gymnastics, athletics, swimming,
synchronized swimming, and fencing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Direct Air Links Between New Zealand, Chile Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Ambassador to Chile
David Mckee has urged Air New Zealand to consider the expansion
of its service to Chile.
</P>
<P>
He said in Auckland Thursday that New Zealand has invested 8
billion New Zealand dollars (4.16 billion U.S. dollars) in Chile
and last year did 70 million New Zealand dollars (36.4 million
U.S. dollars) worth of trade with the country, but it still has no
daily or direct flight connections between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Home on mid-term leave two years into his four-year posting,
the ambassador said travelers and cargo still have to go through
Los Angeles. "A nonstop flight to Santiago would take less than 10
hours," he argued
</P>
<P>
He blamed the transport inconvenience as one of the major
factors which are hindering the two countries in furthering their
economic and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
Some New Zealand investments have experienced difficulties in
the last year in Chile, Mckee said. "NZ Salmon sold its fisheries
interest, Fletcher Challenge Construction decided against pursuing
a planned gypsum project, DML abandoned its goldmining operations
in Chile and Bolivia, Sanford wrote off the book value of its
investment there and Fulton Hogan closed its Chilean office."
</P>
<P>
He said that Carter Holt Harvey has also been through some
stormy times with its joint venture partner, Angelini.
</P>
<P>
But, Mckee said that the positives had to be balanced against
the negatives.
</P>
<P>
New investment and trade opportunities were opening up despite
the market being less buoyant in Chile because of direct and
indirect effects of the Asian economic crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
He cited the recent approval of beef cut sales to Chile from
New Zealand after the signing of a veterinarian agreement. Apart
from the veterinarian agreement, an open skies agreement had also
been cemented, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Preliminary talks have been held on a bilateral investment
protection agreement," he said, adding that the agreement would
not be done through till one between Argentina and New Zealand had
been finalized.
</P>
<P>
Mckee noted that the investment protection agreement was only
one of things being discussed between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said that New Zealand's investment in Chile was
the second biggest after that in Australia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
