<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Opposes Syrian-Iraqi Pipeline Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States Thursday
opposed an agreement between Iraq and Syria to build a second oil
pipeline between the two countries and reopen an old one,
insisting that is inconsistent with U.N. sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters that both
Iraq and Syria had been informed of the U.S position, and said
Washington would "expect the Syrian government to live up to the
sanctions, imposed upon Iraq by the Security Council."
</P>
<P>
There is a pipeline now used for U.N. sanctions programs that
permit Iraq to sell some of its oil to buy food and medicine for
the Iraqi people. The existing pipeline has a capacity of 1.2
million barrels a day. Rubin said that if greater capacity were
needed under the oil-for-food exceptions to the sanctions, the
United Nations would have to give its approval.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed Tuesday in Damascus, Syria, during a
three-day visit by Iraq's Oil Minister Amer Mohammed Rashid, the
Iraqi News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, work would begin soon on the new pipeline,
which Rashid said would have more capacity than the existing one.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency said that Syria and Iraq also agreed to
reopen an old pipeline, which remained closed since 1992 when
Syria joined in the 1991 Gulf war against Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
