<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Black Civil War Soldiers Remembered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Black soldiers during the Civil
War were remembered by descendants at a ceremony Thursday as
heroes who marched for freedom and equality.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony at Arlington National Cemetery was the first event
in a three-day celebration leading to the dedication Saturday of a
monument to the 208,943 black Union soldiers and their white
officers.
</P>
<P>
Black men uniformed in the dark blue of the Union Army took
turns reading citations of the dozens of black soldiers and
sailors awarded the Congressional Medal of Honor during the war.
</P>
<P>
"They knew America was not a perfect country, but they had
strong hopes that the flaws would mend one day," said keynote
speaker Willie L. Hensley, director of the Center for Minority
Veterans in the Department of Veterans Affairs.
</P>
<P>
"These were soldiers who would rather die fighting than die as
slaves," he said. "They fought for respect, for acceptance, for
citizenship.... They were tested at every turn, in more than 40
major engagements.... And even as they fought, their relatives
were being harassed, persecuted and even hanged."
</P>
<P>
More than 37,000 black soldiers died in the Civil War, Hensley
said. More than 4,000 of them are buried at Arlington under stones
that bear the initials USCT for "U.S. Colored Troops."
</P>
<P>
The central statue of the memorial, "Spirit of Freedom,"
depicts the head of an advancing column of black soldiers. It will
be unveiled at a site near Howard University in a predominantly
black neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
The surrounding granite walls and metal plaques bearing the
names of all black soldiers and sailors of the Civil War era are
expected to be in place by Veteran's Day, November 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sees No Quick End to Sanctions on India, Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States said Thursday
that the authority to waive sanctions the Clinton administration
is seeking does not mean an imminent end to sanctions imposed on
India and Pakistan for their nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
"Let me be very clear. We are seeking authority to waive
sanctions. There has not been a decision by the United States to
eliminate sanctions imposed as a result of the India and Pakistani
tests," State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Senate Wednesday approved by voice vote legislation that
would give President Bill Clinton the authority up to one year to
waive sanctions against India and Pakistan. That would give
Clinton flexibility in pursuing his foreign policy, U.S. officials
said.
</P>
<P>
"We want authority to waive sanctions so that we would have the
flexibility in our dealing with India and Pakistan to help us meet
our objectives," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that flexibility in pursuing foreign policy
does not mean lifting or easing sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"We are not walking back from our sanctions policy toward India
or Pakistan, or lifting or easing them and nor is it correct that
lifting or easing of sanctions is imminent," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If granted waiver authority of the type now under
consideration, the administration would not, I emphasize the word
not, be prepared to use such authority in whole or in part until
there has been substantial" change in their position, Rubin added.
</P>
<P>
That would require progress toward meeting demands by the five
existing nuclear powers and the G-8 industrialized states,
including a commitment not to carry out any more tests or to make
nuclear weapons or more fissile materials.
</P>
<P>
"Then and only then would we be in a position to consider
waiving, in whole or in part, the sanctions that are now in
place," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
The United States imposed the sanctions against India and
Pakistan after they conducted nuclear tests in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
