<DOCNO> XIE19980717.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Takes Secret Service Testimony Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The White House Thursday asked
Chief Justice William Rehnquist of the Supreme Court to intervene
after the U.S. Court of Appeals refused to stop Secret Service
officers from testifying in the Monica Lewinsky probe.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department filed the request at the Supreme Court
less than an hour after the appeals court refused to reconsider an
earlier decision ordering the Secret Service personnel, including
President Bill Clinton's chief bodyguard, to testify.
</P>
<P>
The department's "likelihood of success before the Supreme
Court is insufficient to warrant further delay in the grand jury's
investigation," the appeals court said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the appeals court had issued an emergency
order blocking the testimony until the full court made its
decision.
</P>
<P>
Agent Larry Cockell, who oversees the president's security
detail, and the uniformed officers had arrived at the courthouse
Thursday morning prepared to testify before the last-minute legal
struggle began.
</P>
<P>
The temporary stay will expire and the Secret Service personnel
will be forced to testify unless Rehnquist intervenes by the noon
Friday deadline.
</P>
<P>
One of the appeals judges, Laurence Silberman, issued a
separate concurring opinion that suggested the Justice Department
was making its appeals in the personal interest of Clinton rather
than the government.
</P>
<P>
Silberman said he realized the Justice Department comes "under
terrible political pressures and strains of conscience... when the
president's agents literally and figuratively declare war on the
independent counsel."
</P>
<P>
But White House spokesman Mike McCurry said, "War is a very
precise term of art around here; the commander in chief takes that
seriously. We are not at war with Ken Starr but we have some
serious disagreements with him, obviously," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's court decision lets stand an earlier ruling by a
three-judge panel of the appeals court that had ordered the Secret
Service personnel to answer Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's
questions before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
The administration had asked the full court to reconsider that
decision, prompting the order Thursday. It has tried to argue that
the agents are entitled to a new "protective function privilege"
that should exempt them from testifying.
</P>
<P>
But the appeals court rejected the argument, and the Justice
Department took the case to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Justice lawyers had sent protective paperwork to the Supreme
Court that would ask Rehnquist to block the testimony and take the
case when the high court returns to work in October.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson
refused to block the testimony by Cockell and eight uniformed
Secret Service officers who had been subpoenaed by Starr. That
prompted the appeal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
